Other than that, kids love them, I can reach over and pop a dvd in and out from player (s), use control to turn up or lower volume or do anything else from remote. Have not used headphones or played video games on them yet ( kids are too young, and daddy doesn't have time to play anymore....).Still, another bummer is that their "instructions " they provided are non-existant- by that I mean they only show you how to hook up the dvd mounts to the back of the head rests, which is easy. Hmmmm what else...? No battery hook up, only plugs into car adapter for both units...so two outlets needed in car. Besides hook up issue, I do love them and they are sleek and pretty thin for in- car dvd players, which is nice and what I was looking for...and loads the dvd from top. top_review: Pros:- Really comfortable to hold- Good textured feel on the back, I can't imagine dropping this thing by accident unless I consciously tried to- Weight is light but not cheap-feeling, compared to my PS4 controller which is light as well, but doesn't feel as premium- The stellar shift is by far the most beautiful design imo -- totally worth the 1 week wait without prime.- Pairs flawlessly with PC with no further action required on your part, just turn on pairing mode by holding down the pairing button on the front of the controller for 3 secs and Windows should just detect it and prompt you to pair.- Also pairs automatically to Steam which is my original use case for this device.- Buttons feel sturdy and tactile. While PS4 controller wasn't mushy by any means, this thing blows it out of the water.Cons:- Price, it's a bit expensive but if you're playing a lot of controller heavy games then this is probably the best one on the market imo, especially if you're a Steam gamer.- D pad i feel is in a weird place compared to what I'm used to on the Steam Deck and PS4 controller, but that may be just because I've never used an XBOX controller before. This will probably subside as I get used to the layout and is nitpicking at worst.Overall a pretty good buy. Gonna keep testing it out but right now I am playing Honkai Star Rail and it works flawlessly.

title: Fstop Labs 2 Pack Wall Ceiling Cabinet Mount Holder Stand Clip for Google Nest Home Mini Gen 1, Gen 2, Round Speaker Accessories (White) 2 Pack
top_review: Highly recommend this mount!Although relatively easy to install, I have really flimsy apartment walls that don't really grab on to nails and screws too well. I gave it 4 stars for "easy to install" because I had to remove the hardware and screw the screws into the little pegs all the way tightly to secure them to the mount before using a hammer to finish the job. It took all of less than 5 minutes. After that, it won't budge and very sturdily grips my mini. I'd suggest to plug it in after bringing the cord through the little hole at the bottom of the mount before clipping it into position.Overall, this mount is the most solid of the 3 or 4 I've owned thus far. My mini kind of just "floats" on the wall and the mount is pretty much invisible with just the cord hanging down.The device is responding much better to voice commands now that it's not muffled on my desk or knocked over by my curious cat!child. (Or at least she hasn't jumped at it yet. She's kinda more interested in the boxes from having recently moved!)This mount has also made the speaker sound quality a whole lot better and it actually fills my entire apartment at even 60% volume. Since the clip rests behind the fabric part, access to the physical controls/buttons is very easy and touching it for volume is completely unhindered. The mount stays perfectly out of the way while still securing the device to the wall.As with any wall mount where the power cord is on the bottom, make sure to flip the LEDs & volume controls in the Google Home app or your flashy lights will be backwards. Just go into the device settings and the option is near the bottom under "Reverse device controls".A very affordable little solution that's just exactly what I was looking for!

title: Wii U Gamepad Silicone Jacket - Black
availability: Only 1 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: The GamePad is the distinguishing feature of Nintendo's Wii U.  It will also be relatively expensive to replace.  (At the time of this writing, it is not even sold separate of the Wii U console, itself.)  It behooves one to afford it a reasonable amount of protection.  This silicone skin from PDP fits the bill, perfectly.The skin fits quite snugly over the GamePad and once on, does not feel flimsy or move about on the device.  It is not something I would want to remove and reapply on a regular basis, but thanks to PDP's thoughtful design, you don't have to:  this skin leaves exposed the portion of the GamePad that contacts the charging cradle, allowing the skin to remain on at all times (even when docked.)The material is not your typical silicone formula.  It has a much smoother feel, and does not attract lint like typical silicone.  Once applied to the GamePad, it has a feel of almost rubberized plastic or matte TPU material.  That is to say that it has a feeling of quality.  While the top portion is smooth to the touch, the underside has a slightly dimpled texture that aids in the gripping of the device; the texture is not unlike that of an orange peel.The buttons are all exposed and perfectly aligned, and while the skin does cause them to be recessed slightly, I find that it does not hinder their functionality whatsoever.Something not depicted in the product photos is the Wii U logo and the NFC marker (the rounded rectangle) which are painted in white on the skin in the same places as on the GamePad, itself.  As these are design elements of the actual GamePad, it is a tasteful addition to the product.  (To PDP's credit, they did not attempt to include their own logo or branding on the skin.)I am impressed by PDP's offering, and I can say that this is the most ideal skin/cover for the Wii U GamePad that I have encountered (and I have tried several.)  I can say that I highly recommend this product; if you are seeking protection for your GamePad, look no further.

title: USB C Hub, TOTU 6 in 1 USB C Adapter with 4K HDMI Output, VGA, SD/TF Card Reader, 2 USB 3.0 for USB C Laptops and Other Type C Devices
availability: Only 7 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: I got a new laptop to replace an older desktop that had run its course.  I wanted to have the functionality and power of my desktop with fixed network, video, and USB connectivity  and the ability to easily disconnect the laptop and take it with me.  I also needed to support two external 27” HD monitors.  Being able to also support the laptop screen for a 3rd screen was also desired.  The laptop by itself only supported a single HDMI connection in addition to its screen.  After research, this USB-C 11 in 1 docking solution from  TOTU met my requirements with a single USB-C connection providing the fixed Video, USB, and Network connectivity that I required.The unit has an HDMI and VGA video connection which is nice for flexibility in monitor connections.  Both support my monitor’s 1920 x 1280 HD resolution.  I didn’t have a display, cable, or 4K TV to test the full 4K resolution.  There was a limitation with my laptop when using both ports (HDMI and VGA) at the same time from this device where both displays would only operate in duplicate display mode (where the same thing is displayed on both  ports).  This is a minor negative as I still can support both of my external displays using the HDMI from the laptop in addition to either of these ports.  I understood this limitation prior to purchasing as it was mentioned in the specifications.The ethernet port is a Realtek USB GbE connection and worked well. I don’t know how to test its performance and bandwidth but It's more than enough to cover my internet speed of 50Mbs. All USB 2.0 ports and 3.0 ports worked as expected and its nice to have the extra ports to plug in my fixed keyboard and mouse as well as an external hard drive for backups.  I also tested the SD card port and it worked well.Something to be aware of before purchasing.  To support video from this device, your laptop must support Alt mode for video over the USB-C port.  The best way to know this is to refer to your laptop specifications.  Many will state the USB-C port is data only.  If the USB-C is Thunderbolt or Displayport support then video will work with this USB-C hub device.  One way I found to know if it is Thunderbolt or Displayport capable, the port will have a lightning bolt symbol next to the port or a Display Port symbol (which looks like a P inside of a D) next to the port. (google display port symbol to know what this looks like)  Just be aware, not all laptops with a USB-C port support video.  This is not a limitation of the TOTU USB hub but a limitation of the laptop.There are a few minor flaws:  As state earlier, both video ports used simultaneously will only work in duplicate display mode.  If you need both to work as individual monitors, this may not work for you.  For me, this was OK as I still was able to use the laptop HDMI port to get my second external monitor connection.The second minor flaw was  the LED’s on the ethernet port.  These are always on and do not change if an ethernet cable is plugged in or not.  They give no indication of link, activity, or ethernet speed.  Again, the ethernet port works. The LEDs simply do appear to serve any purpose..Overall, this USB-C docking hub met all of my expectations and is a good docking solution with only one or two connections needed to have all the connectivity of my previous desktop with the portability of a laptop.

title: Topsung Walkie Talkies Rechargeable, 4 Pack Easy to Use Long Range Walky Talky for Adult Handheld Two Way Radio with NOAA for Hiking Camping (Orange&Blue&Green&Silver with Micro-USB Charger/Battery)
top_review: We purchased a set of 3 as a Christmas gift for our young kids! Our boys are 4 and 6 and we wanted a third unit for mom or dad. We tried a few “kids” walkie talkies (about $30 for three units) found they went out of range much sooner than we’d like—then we ordered these. The sound quality and range on these was much better so we didn’t mind paying more (about $50 for 3 units).I also really love that these are rechargeable, because we would burn through batteries quickly!About a month after opening them, one unit started malfunctioning—squelch stopped working so there was constant static unless someone was signaling. After a factory reset it stopped communicating with the other units at all. The seller was very responsive, first troubleshooting the problem and finally replacing the unit.My boys are still a bit young for them and the younger one in particular has trouble remembering to hold/release the talk button at the appropriate times. For now, we most often use them on bike rides (kids on bikes, mama on foot). I set their radios to be sound activated and clip them to their bikes, and the boys can hear me and respond. Since I can’t keep up with them I really appreciate being able to coach or give instructions when they are too far ahead to hear me.

title: Eyoyo 12 inch HD 1920x1080 IPS LCD HDMI Monitor Screen Input Audio Video Display with BNC Cable for PC Computer Camera DVD Security CCTV DVR Home Office Surveillance
availability: Only 8 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: I got this based on the resolution and the many types of video inputs it supports. What I got was something I have been using every day since it arrived for various things including troubleshooting my recent computer rebuild before securing it all together since moving it to the main monitor I was using was a bit too far for me to run a cable.The HDMI works great with any device I've throw at it including Display Port to HDMI or just strait HDMI from a computer, HDMI from the SNES Classic and Raspberry Pi 3, and of course HDMI from my Blu-ray Player indicating this monitor has proper HDCP support for encrypted signals. I also tested VGA from one of my older computers and while it saw higher resolutions then what the screen actually supported (possible fix with a firmware update if one is to ever exist for it) it did support up to 1080p 60Hz without issue and a really good picture with clearly readable text even with such a small screen.Sound is nothing too impressive but it does have a headphone jack and the USB port stays powered no matter what input it's set to so a good set of USB powered speakers can be used to substitute it but I found that is not the fault of the speakers themselves but rather the construction of the case which makes them sound a bit hollow. I opened mine up to see if I could somehow see about fixing that with maybe installing better speakers and found the sound improved when they were exposed to more open air. Not sure what that could mean for a possible fix but something to note at least. They are rear facing and proper stereo but they do get pretty loud and in fact there were a few times when lowering the volume to 1 the sound was still just a tad bit too loud for what I was looking for but that's better then being too quiet even with the volume maxed out as many modern TVs tend to have an issue with. If anyone happens to know of something I could insert behind the speakers to help direct more of the sound and improve the bass sound a bit that would be welcome advice.The final test I gave it was to see how it handled classic video game consoles due to certain odd behaviors like when characters flicker when being hit. My larger LCD TV tends to have issues with such things often making the character vanish or remain solid depending on the frame the flicker starts at but this screen seemed to handle that without much issue but other effects didn't always behave as expected but never had the invisible issue I sort of had to get used to with my larger TV so overall a decent composite upscaler in that regard if not perfect. This monitor also supports PAL signals but I have yet to test that though I'm sure it will work just as fine so that makes it great for people who don't want to be limited to the TV standard of whichever country they happen to live in.The only thing I couldn't figure out was how to use was the MIC port on it. I assumed it would allow for some kind of analog audio input beyond that of he composite video connection such as audio input for the VGA mode but no matter what I tried I couldn't seem to get it to play anything I fed to it. The instructions sadly seemed more concerned with going over every part of the on screen menu options and not a single section even mentioned all the different inputs and what they were for other then a page that talked about it's supported resolutions and formats for playing media from USB.The buttons on the back can be a bit confusing but there is a picture in the manual which clears things up a bit showing that  what most would call the up and down buttons are actually the left and right buttons which control the volume as well and even the included remote which has dedicated volume buttons will also adjust the volume with the left and right directional buttons just like those on the back of the monitor.I didn't do too much testing of the media playback but the fact it supports MKV files is interesting as that is a format you don't often see support for in devices like this. If a USB drive is inserted already when switching to the USB mode it will automatically start playing media from the first folder it sees. Again I didn't do too much testing of this just yet and never did see what it would do if you switched to USB and then connected a drive or how it determined the "first folder" though I assume it's alphabetical and you can just open the playback controls with the OK button and choose Stop to go back to the folder display and choose what you want to play yourself from there.There are no media controls on the remote and as such this monitor does not appear to have support for HDMI-CEC which is a shame but not the end of the world so if that is something you are looking for sadly you will need to find a different solution. That would have been quite a nice feature for use with say a Raspberry Pi with Kodi or OpenPlex to use as a tiny local media streaming player.I have seen older reviews mentioning uneven backlight and such but either I got lucky or they have managed to fix those issues with these newer monitors as it seems fairly even for me with barely noticeable spotlighting on the edges in a couple spots which are easily ignored with casual viewing. Overall not a bad purchase for what this thing is capable of. The only thing I wish it had was a digital TV tuner or a built-in rechargeable battery to be a truly perfect, portable monitor but I at least got me a nice 3000mah rechargeable 12 volt USB battery pack to have one of my two wishes for it come true and I get quite a few hours of use on a full charge with it. I can see me using this for a lot of things in the near future maybe even beyond what I've tried it for already.

title: Hitachi Ultrastar A7K3000 2TB HUA723020ALA641 (0F12470) 2TB 64MB Cache 7200RPM SATA III (6.0Gb/s) Enterprise 3.5in Hard Drive (Renewed)
top_review: Some commenters have rightly questioned the wisdom of running a refurbished drive without clear history as a storage device for a live computer.  I personally would not do that other than in a RAID system.I bought one of these refurbished Untrastar 2 TB drives to use as a third backup set.  My other two backups are also 2 TB Ultrastars for which I gladly paid close to $200 each a couple of years ago.  I believe that having multiple redundant "air gapped" backups is especially important with the recent rise in "ransomware" attacks that hit every storage device attached to a computer.I was hesitant to buy this drive based on the principle that it looked too good to be true.  But I risked less than $50, and I am not disappointed in any way.  This drive will sit in my safe most of the time, coming out about once per week to touch up the backup set with my latest files.My five-star rating is provisional because I have spun up this drive only once.  I initialized and formatted it on my Windows 10 machine, and ran a complete backup of the three volumes (all SSD) in the box.  The OS has reported no errors on the drive.  It runs very quiet, and write performance over a USB 3 to SATA adapter was as I expected.  Should the drive start giving me problems over the next two, three, or several years I may revise the score downward.  For now I have no reason to give it less than a top score.Three backup sets provides me significantly more peace of mind than two did.

title: Underwater Camera, UHD 4K 48MP Autofocus Waterproof Camera with 16X Zoom Selfie Dual Screens,11FT Compact Waterproof Digital Camera with 64GB Card,Fill Light Underwater Camera for Snorkeling(Blue)
top_review: First of all, this camera is as advertised. After we got it, we spent the day at the beach and pool playing around with it. The camera had no problem being in the water for hours at a time, and the images are fantastic! We shot video at 4K and the stills at 48MP. The video is slightly jerky so when you use it for shooting motion, keep the camera movement to a minimum. We made our own selfie stick to hold the camera underwater for smooth video.The digital zoom works well and is easy to use. It has a monitor on the front of the camera for selfies, also very easy to access. The camera has many special effects which is really fun for my son to play with. It is very small and compact allowing you to take it anywhere very easily. Getting used to the menu takes a little time, but once you spend some time with it, it starts to get more familiar.Two batteries are included which is very helpful. We always keep two batteries charged when going out with the camera. Charging is done with the battery in the camera using the supplied USB cable and power brick. The battery life for each charge lasts a pretty long time.There are several settings for picture quality, I would recommend using the highest setting of 48MP, which carries a slightly higher file size. Also good lighting helps the images come very close to iPhone quality. With some images, the difference between the two camera is indistinguishable.The camera shoots on a micro SD card which can easily attach to a computer, either connecting the camera to a computer with the supplied cable or using an micro SD card reader, which I purchased on Amazon for $7.Also recommended is a hard shell case, also purchased on Amazon for $16. It’s a worthwhile purchase as my son will throw the camera in his backpack which will get jostled around quite a bit.The camera has the standard thread mount so it can be attached to virtually any tripod or selfie stick.Overall, it’s a great quality camera for the price and the fact that is completely waterproof is a huge bonus, especially if it’s for kids and you don’t have to worry about any damage from water.

top_review: My ONLY caveat is the fact that Onkyo didn't see fit to just put an HDRadio tuner in my PR-SC5508,like they did with my old Integra DTC-9.8.Otherwise this unit works wonderfully and I have HDRadio once again!Washington,D.C's radio stations are almost all HD at this  point.So I have no problems with receiving HD stations.Even with my nearly 30 year old Radio Shack,Archer FM stereo Supreme rabbit ears FM antenna.I just select"port" on the Pre/Pro and listen to my local radio stations in Hybrid Digital(that is what the HD in HDRadio used to stand for.Now it really doesn't stand for anything.It,however has NEVER stood for High Definition,like with HD tv)I can even upgrade the firmware via the PR-SC5508.However the upgrade never seems to"take".READ the directions and FOLLOW THEM.Make SURE you have both AM and FM antenna's hooked up properly.DO NOT use the floppy,wire style FM antenna's if you want to receive adequate HD Digital reception.Those antennae work adequately(barely)for analog FM,but they SUCK for ALL or NOTHING digital reception!!Also AM HD reception never seems to quite equal FM.I wonder what it would be like if I made one of those great,big AM antenna's that they used to publish instructions for in the audio rags...........2014 updateThit unit also works quite well with my Onkyo PR-SC5509 preamp and Integra DTM-40.4 stereo receiver.As well as with the Onkyo TX-8050 receiver that the Integra replaced.Also sucessfully working with a TX-NR709 receiver that a friend owns.And now for my rantI too must agree with some other reviewers here.Do not give this unit a bad review if you didn't follow the instructions or it was damaged in shipping and arrived DOA.That is not Amazon's OR Onkyo's fault!!That is like blaming the city or town you live in for putting in concrete sidewalks when your child falls off their skateboard and hits their head and now has a cuncussion.How ridiculous is that??

top_review: I purchased this 95mm, 16-1/2 stop filter to photograph the upcoming total solar eclipse. No filter is needed for photographing the totality portion of the event, but a solar filter is absolutely necessary for the partial eclipse portions. I have three electronic camera accessories made by Neewer and the quality is top notch, this filter is also very high quality. It is slightly difficult to install and remove due to the very thin aluminum frame. The knurling is on the outside circumference rather than the front edge. As the filter is screwed into the lens, it sinks into the counterbored lens housing of my Nikon 200-500 f/2.8 lens and it’s difficult to get a grip on the filter. A Nikon filter for the same lens has a slightly wider frame with knurling on the front edge. That is my only concern, otherwise it comes in a sturdy lens case with a microfiber lens cloth. It also has some basic recommendations for photographing the eclipse. The optical glass is coated for water, scratch resistant and reflection. I have several high end filters and this one matches up nicely in fit, finish and quality. At the price, this filter is an excellent value. I’m looking forward to photographing the solar eclipse with it on April 8. I have included a photograph of the sun taken with it.

title: Samsung Galaxy Tab A9+ Tablet 11” 64GB Android Tablet, Big Screen, Quad Speakers, Upgraded Chipset, Multi Window Display, Slim, Light, Durable Design, US Version, 2024, Graphite
top_review: I picked the WiFi version up in mid March 2025 for my 6 year old during a special after her tablet was cracked in an accident caused by her sister. I got this because its not exactly top of the line but it has a good balance power and performance, and I read many good reviews on it claiming the very same.When I gave this tablet to my daughter, she was excited. The first thing she noticed was the screen was almost 3 inches bigger than her previous tablet. She was so happy to have a tablet close in size to mine, and from the same company. lol (she's a daddy's girl and Samsung is my thing)She also noticed that her new tablet is so much faster than her previous tablet. She celebrated by downloading some of her favorite games from the google play store that her last tablet could not run without issue. I opted for the 12 GB ram model, which of you decide to pick one up, you should definitely do the same. It made the entire experience of this tablet so much better and smoother.The screen has amazing color richness for what I paid. I honestly figured for the price I paid, this was going to be just another washed out, low spec, disposable tablet. So many of the cheaper new tablets you see these days lack in some areas to justify boosts in others. Didn't take long to find out that this was not the case for this one. While you're not going to be playing games like Genshin Impact or CoD Mobile on ultra high settings, you can play most games on medium and a lot on higher settings with ease.My daughter does not stream movies on her tablet, so widevine support was not one of the specs I worried about when selecting this tablet. If you are into that and need your tablet to stream movies in high resolution, make sure to check the widevine level first. Low support could be a deal breaker for some people.Battery life seems to be quite good. On a full charge, she can usually get multiple days at a few hours per days before needing to plug in. She uses the tablet for everything from school work, light gaming, and her favorite thing.. searching for the definition of words she hears throughout the day and attempting to use them in sentences. Makes for interesting conversations.. lolSince this and many tablets and phones these days do not come with chargers, its best to find a decent one with multiple charging speeds starting at the lowest. Thats what I did and the tablet uses the fastest output that is needed for fast charge, you just need to be sure the charger you pick has multiple speeds if you don'tpick up a specific charger from Samsung. I used a 45w charger that clocks all the way down to charge low demand items, like my headphones. That charges my tablet at 45An additional note: If you decide to get this tablet, be sure to pick up a fast, large capacity Micro SD card. I got myself a Samsung card directly from Samsungs site. I added a Samsung PRO Plus 512 GB microSDXC to my tablet and a 128 to my daughters.Now, the only thing I can honestly say i do not like about the A9+. The camera.. my daughter thinks its great, but she came from a tablet with a barely functioning camera to the A9+. She is just happy to be able to take pictures that don't look they were taken in the deep end of a swimming pool. lolNow if your thing is taking a lot of pictures at good quality, this really is not the device for you. But keep in mind, most of these tablets are not focused on camera quality like today's phones. They put most of their R&D into the hardware specs of the tablet and skimp on the camera quality. You want good quality photos in a tablet, you get a newer iPad or Galaxy S9 or S10 series (minus the FE). The S9 FE is a decent tablet, its just that Samsung spent most of that budget on improved hardware related to performance, not camera quality.

title: Gary Fong LS2C4 Lightsphere II Cloud Size 4 (Translucent)
availability: Only 1 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: Ich nutze den Lightspere II C4 Cloud auf bereits 2 Canon 580EX II Blitzen, sowie den neuen Whaletail auf einen dritten 580EX II. Ich arbeite als Fotograf in alle Bereichen. Von Hochtzeitsfotografie, bis hin zur Produktfotografie.Ich war es leid ständig mein schweres Porty mit der gesamten Studioblitzanlage durch die Gegend zu schleppen. Von daher suchte ich ein Diffusorsystem was die ganze Sache mit Systemblitzen ersetzt (zumindest in Teilbereichen... ist ja klar).Das so ein 580 EXII nicht soviel Bums hat wie ein großer Studioblitz ist logisch (Diffusoren minimieren die Blitzleistung zudem locker ab 2 Blenden aufwärts), wenn es aber nur darum geht Schatten aufzuhellen, oder ein Portrait in geschlossenen Räumen in Studioqualität zu erstellen, ist er sehr gut geeignet. Auch im Außenbereich spielt er seine Stärken gegenüber einem Durchlichtschirm auf Grund seiner Kompaktheit aus. (Ein Stativ mit Durchlichtschirm muss man immer beschweren, sonst kippt die Geschichte bei leichten Windstößen sehr schnell um, also wieder schleppen...) Ein großer noch nicht von mir genannter Vorteil ist die gute Ausleuchtung unter Ausnutzung der Umgebung, wenn Wände für die Licht - Reflexion vorhanden sind. Der C4 Cloud gibt das Licht, wenn man den Blitz nach oben richtet, sehr gleichmäßig ab, wobei nur sehr softe Schatten entstehen. Richtet man den Blitz nach vorne aus, hat man mehr gerichtetes Licht, welches aber immer noch sehr weich rüber kommt. Also alles in Allem eine gute Alternative, mit Kompromissen, eine sehr schöne Ausleuchtung hin zu bekommen. Wer sich für solch einen Diffusor interessiert sollte aber nicht vorher am Blitz gespart haben. Ein kleinerer Blitz als der 580 EX sollte es bei solch einem Aufsatz möglichst nicht sein. Man erreicht zu schnell das Ende der benötigten Lichtleistung.Noch ein kleiner Tipp: Wer mit dem Gedanken spielt ein 430 EX II  zu kaufen, sollte lieber auf einen gebrauchten 580 EX der ersten Generation ausweichen. Von Preis nimmt sich das nichts, von der Leistung dagegen sehr.In der Hoffnung mit meinem Beitrag weiter helfen zu können verbleibe ich mitfreundlichen GrüssenFDS-Fotodesign

title: VFENG Premium 6 in 1 3M Vinyl Skin Cover for 2016+ MacBook Pro 13" with Function Keys(Model: A1708), with 2 Pack Screen Protector-Silver
availability: Only 1 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: This is incredible, magic stuff! Perfect for the gray MacBook Pro 13”.I found that if I centered the logo, the edge dangled off on the side just a smidge. So I focused on the left side and corners first. The logo ended up not being exact, and the right side dangled over just a smidge but not too bad.SOOOO… after applying the front, when doing the back I found that the material actually stretches a bit, and that the best way to apply it is to focus on all the key areas (rubber feet, screw holes) and gently tap them into place, and the rub out any remaining air bubbles. That’s where the magic comes in… the air bubbles just disappear! You don’t have to rub them to an edge to let the air escape — it just magically disappears, presumably through the 3M material itself! So get the key areas tapped down and then just rub out any remaining air bubbles. I’ve never applied such a film – truly amazing (3M products always amaze me).I wish I had known this before doing the front, so I recommend doing the back first to get the hang of it.Truly excellent protection for the MacBook… my wife was dubious, saying “I’ll just use a sleeve,” but when doing the front I told her “you’ve already got a scuff on the front that won’t wipe off” and she was shocked. So get this stuff on asap to protect your MacBook!Oh, and the trackpad works perfectly fine with the film attached. title: UYIYE Kickstand Case for Steam Deck - Protective and Reliable Accessory with Stand Function
top_review: Looks great and fits perfectly. Exactly what I wanted. However there are some minor quirks to be aware of before purchase.1. The touchpads are perfectly flush with the case under a slight recess. This isn't an issue for me and I have full control and touch capacity, but it does merrit some notice.2. It gives the letter buttons a slightly recessed feel. For me this isnt an obstruction however I can see how it may affect some players.3. It makes the SD slot a bit difficult to access. This is kinda an obvious thing but worth mention.Aside from those three things I cant really make any negative notes. The pleather is soft but not too soft, the fit has no wiggle so there is no rattle from the case, and the port cutouts allow me to use my dock and the charging cable that comes with the steamdeck.Now, I do see other reviews calling this out. To note I am not using the official steam deck, I am using one by ivanki, and I am using the oled model. The latter has no affect on things since both models are the same design and size.The official dock though is a form fitting connector with that little piece on the wire side which will cause issue. Make of this detail what you will.Update 6/26 - So, its been about 8 months. Im still using this case, but there are a few things to point out. There are two weak points to this case. In hindsight, its pretty obvious but the snapping tabs that keep the case close are good at what they do. However, as with some brands of laptops, they do not take well to being opened. Often this means a broken tab. The second fault is the stand. I've added a photo regarding but to explain a bit more It isnt really built to be pushed back. Just the weight of the deck kinda forces it to stress a bit. If something somehow pushed it all the way to the top it would barely survive. Honestly, with a plastic case, there isnt exactly a means of fixing this without making both case and metal on stand thicker, which just would feel just too chunky.

availability: In stock Usually ships within 3 to 4 days.
top_review: Let me preface this by noting I have used the Godox X1Ts extensively, and now this Xpro-S for almost a month now, and I must say the upgrade was worth it.I have been using this on a Sony A7R3 as well as a Sony a6300, and it works great.  Compared to the X1T, this has a much larger screen, easier to access buttons, and the operation is a little simpler.  What I also like is that when I adapted my old larger Canon lenses, the X1T wouldn't allow all the lenses to fit due to the overhang on the X1T, however since the XPro trigger is angled up, I was able to use my larger adapted lenses without issue.I paired this up with the Godox 350, 685 as well as a FP400 and had no issues with triggering.  Out of about 500 shots in a session, I had two misfires but one might have been me and the power settings I had on my FP400.  I tested both TTL as well as manual and HSS and it was very consistent and reliable.  The only thing I think might need a little work is the battery indicator seems to be only accurate for alkaline cells, but for me it isn't a big deal at all.  My fully charged niMh batteries indicated half, but my full alkaline cells showed accurately.For the value for the money, this is a no-brainer if you want a good and reliable trigger.

title: SABRENT USB 3.0 mSATA II or III/5GBp/s SSD Enclosure Adapter [Support UASP] (EC-UKMS)
top_review: Very nice, small piece of equipment, for a good price.I ended up buying two of them because I was worried about reliability. I tested them out somewhat extensively and both seem to work as advertised. Long term, I'm unsure of how they will hold up, but they seem legit. Hopefully I can address a few complaints that I read in the reviews.The design is nice and simple, clean, and appears to be machined well. It doesn't have a big, glowing logo on the front of it like some designs, which I'm really happy about. It's TINY. I would prefer a shorter USB cable, but don't mind the one supplied. It's short enough for my needs. Even the tiny LED light is unobtrusive, unlike some items where the LED lights up a dark room.I'm using it with a Samsung 1TB EVO 850 mSATA drive, with a 2015 13" Macbook Pro. I cloned my internal 1Tb drive to the external one, copying about 650Gb, which took over an hour to complete. That may sound like a long time, at about 180MB/s, but I'll explain that later...After the drive was cloned, I booted from the external mSATA drive without a problem in both of my enclosure units (just swapped out the SSD).The enclosure gets hot. Obviously. It's supposed to get hot. That means it's doing it's job properly as a heatsink. With the amount of data I was transferring, I shutter to think how hot the Samsung "T1" drive would get with it's plastic casing. Plastic is an excellent insulator, and aluminum is a much better choice as a heatsink. If anyone is unaware of the Samsung T1, look it up. I was trying to replicate that, except with better components.The enclosure got too hot to the touch midway through the cloning process. After touching the device for about 5-8 seconds, it became too unbearable to touch. It didn't really burn me, just was painful, and not unlike the heat produced by my spinning mechanical drives.While it was running at that temperature, copy speeds seemed to be about 150MB/s. I believe this is due to the Samsung 1TB EVO 850 design that intentionally throttles the write / read speed to protect itself. I had read that drives of less capacity in the EVO 850 line perform a lot better because they don't get so hot (something about power management).Things got interesting when I placed the drive on top of a piece of thin aluminum as an additional heatsink. The drive almost instantly cooled to the point where I could hold it in my hand. After that, copy speed picked up visibly. I'm sure that in a pinch, if you needed to work that drive hard, you could place it on some aluminum foil and that could further dissipate the heat.For my purposes, I'm using it for data back up when I travel. So all of my media should be backed up and in my pocket at all times, unless of course I'm using the laptop. I always keep the two copies of files in separate places in the event of theft. This little 1TB mSATA drive is going to be AWESOME for that, and fat better than my old LaCie rugged mechanical drives.If you want to use this as an external boot drive, I'd recommend going with a more traditional format, since these small form factor drives are not really meant to be in an environment without adequate cooling.If you are like me and you want a tiny little USB drive that can hold 1TB of data that you occasionally need to read and write to, look no further. A Samsung 500GB mSATA SSD may be even better if you don't need the capacity.

top_review: I have bought a lot of very expensive amps that arent built as well as this one, specially for the price. All the connections are well laid out, all the controls are easily adjusted, the body is well built and very clean looking. The manual is very well written and easily understood with a lot more info than a lot of higher priced models. I have been running this amp bridged at 2 Ohms for a week now, it has performed flawlessly without overheating even once, I have it mounted in a pretty tight area that doesnt get much air circulation, in fact I had an MTX amp mounted in the same spot and it would constantly overheat and go into protection. As far as sound quality goes it sounds very good! No noise, very clean and solid bass, I am able to play it far louder than the MTX and Rockford Fosgate it replaced, it actually sounds like it was made to listen to not just to make speakers go boom. I listen to music not Rap and it sounds very smooth no matter what I play. Drums sound like drums, bass guitars sound like guitars not like a horrible low frequency buzz. I was so happy with the quality that I bought a SSL EV4.400 four channel amp for my mids and tweets, I also bought a SSL S4EQ to control everything. If these units last a month with the punishment I give them I will be buying more SSL products. It's nice to know someone makes a quality amp that doesnt cost a fortune! I wouldnt hesitate to recomend this amp to anyone looking for a quality product at a very good price!

title: MAYFLASH W004 Ps2 Controller Adapter for Wii/Wii U Remote
availability: Only 1 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: There are some Wii games that can be played with a Wii Classic Controller. Odd that the Classic Controller looks very similar to a PS2 Dual Shock. I have so many PS1 and PS2 controllers that I really did not need another controller just for the Wii. I already have a couple of PS2 to Gamecube adaptors and wanted to play Wii games this way. Discovered the Mayflash Adaptor thru a Google search.What I like about the PSX to Wii adaptor is it plugs right in the remote and is hot swapable, no need to reboot the Wii. All the Playstation controllers become wireless in a sense in that they are not direct attached to the Wii.Turbo Button for Auto FireFor setting up to eight buttons on the Playstation controller in rapid fire. Simply hold the Turbo button on the Mayflash and press a button on the PSX controller to enable. Now when an enabled button is pressed the Mayflash will flicker the LED. To disable Auto Fire simply hold the Mayflash Turbo buton and tap the PSX button again. Auto Fire only works on the PSX controllers and only on Wii games that support the Classic controller.So how does an Analog sticks compare to the Remote? I tested a standard PS2 Dual Shock controller. A Wii Classic Controller has almost the same layout as a PSX controller. So both should work almost identically.PSX ......................................... WiiStart .......................................... +Select ......................................... -Gamepad ........................ GamepadAnalog Sticks .............. Analog SticksX .............................................. bO .............................................. aSQUARE ..................................... yTRiANGLE ................................... xR1 ........................................... ZRR2 ............................................. RL1 ............................................ ZLL2 .............................................. LR3 L3 .................................. HomeWii Opening MenuThe PSX Analog sticks mover the cursor around okay, but the remote is a quicker "Light" gun response. So much simpler to point with the Remote for accuracy. Both the Remote and PSX controllers still work, point the remote away from the Sensor Bar to use a PSX controller.Geometry WarsThe Robotron inspired twinstick game with "Vector" graphics like Black Widow. The Remote works great, but now with a Dual Analog, its even better! One analog stick moves the ship while the other analog stick controls the rapid Fire shots. Nice moving one direction while shooting in another. Note that Rapid Fire is in the game itself, the Mayflash Turbo is only for the buttons.Arcade TwinstickAt first I was disappointed that the gamepad and four Face buttons are not utilized on the Dual Shock. This would kill using any PSX Digital Arcade Stick. I plugged in my Two Player Arcade Blaze Twin Shock just to see what would happen.Flawless accurate gameplay control! Twinstick Heaven!The digital stick actually works!!! The Arcade stick acts just like the left Analog stick and the four face buttons default to the right analog stick of Geometry Wars. Very strange considering that the Stick normally defaults to the direction pad on a regular Playstation. This is perfect considering that I have modded the Player Two stick to operate as the face buttons of Player One. Geometry Wars is played just like the Arcade game Robotron, not with tiny thumbsticks, but full sized Arcade Sticks!So was Geometry Wars the only game that offered the unique Digital Twin Stick mode? I have another game to test and see if this was just a lucky chance.Sin & PunishmentStrange that the game case does not show the Classic Controller Icon on the back cover. The original N64 import used one Analog stick for aiming and the buttons for sideways movement. Wii actually plays better with a Remote for aiming and the Nunchuck for full movement. Now to try out the PS2 controller.The PS2 Dual Shock works after I adjusted the settings menu to a better button layout. Left Analog stick moves the gunsight, the Right Analog stick moves the character. Trigger buttons are the weapons and evade. Works great, though the Wii Remote does offer a quick instant point to where you want to shoot.The modded Blaze Arcade Twinstick also works just like the Dual Shock. After reconfiguring the game settings, Player One stick is the gunsite, the four face buttons are for movement which is also controlled by the modded player two stick. The trigger buttons are set for weapons and evade. Works okay but a trick tapping the fire buttons with both hands on the Arcade sticks. The Wii Remote is still the best aiming device.Mayflash ValueSo is the Mayflash adaptor better then just going with a Wii Classic Controller? I can't give a true assessment since I don't have one to compare. But the adaptor allows use of all the various controllers that are available on the PS1 and PS2. Some others to try include a Driving Controller, Dance Pad, Flight Sticks and even the unusual ones such as Beatmania and a Densha De Go Train controller. The Playstation has tons of controllers to try with the "Classic Controller" games, offering a different way to play a game.

title: Neewer Metal AF Auto-Focus Macro Extension Tube Set 10mm&16mm for Sony NEX E-Mount Camera NEX 3/3N/5/5N/5R/A6000/A6300 and Full Frame A7 A7S/A7SII A7R/A7RII A7II
top_review: This works great, but something you have to understand is this changes the focal point. For one example I used these on my Sony AIII and a Sony 24mm 1.4GM. To focus on an item you need the front of the lens about 1 inch away from the subject. This is too close if you want to take a picture of a bee or something that is alive. On my Sony 24-70mm 2.8 GM I need to be about 2 inches away to focus on something. The range of 24-70 didn't make much difference. For my last example I used my Sony 85mm 1.8 lens. The minimum focus distance on this lens is pretty far at 2.62 feet (80cm). With this lens I can be about 1 foot away to focus on my subject. Here are some tips; If you use manual focus and focus as close as possible you can get more magnification, and if you focus to infinity you can get less. Also, use the 16mm  extension tube on the camera body first if you are stacking these. If I put the 10m extension tube on the camera, and attach the 16mm on the lens, I get a funny yellow color. If I attach the 16mm tube on the camera body, and then stack the 10mm, the color is fine. For best results I'd use a lens that has a longer minimum focusing distance. I think any of the Sony 70-200mm lenses would work excellent with this kit. I don't have such a lens yet though. Autofocus is pretty good. I took some of my practice shots on a $1 dollar bill and my camera was actually using eye autofocus on George Washington's eyes.

title: 10FT Underwater Camera for Kids, Kids Waterproof Camera, 1080P Video Camera for Snorkeling, Christmas Birthday Gifts Pool Toys for Girls Ages 4-12, Toddler Digital Action Camera with 32GB Card (Pink)
top_review: This is a simple little underwater camera that's fairly intuitive out of the box and sized well for small hands. It's a point and shoot and takes fairly decent pics both in and out of water. The power button is tiny, tiny and hard to see (for adults at least). There are some other fun little things on this camera, simple games to play. We'll be using it simply for picture taking underwater. title: HECO Aurora 700 3-Way, Dual 6.5" Floorstanding Speaker in White Outfitted for Deeper Bass
availability: Only 2 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: I have been searching for a sound that I remember from the 70s. Yeah, I'm old....It started with pre-amps, which lead to cartridges (MC and MM) and then, speakers. I have an OK setup, Fluance 85 table, Parasound Pre and a new Marantz receiver (thank you lightning strike). Finally, my speaker quest. Started with Polk T50 three ways which sounded pretty good at the time but, with the upgraded system, just wasn't hearing the joy (this was when the cartridge rabbit hole opened). Having been in the audio industry, I had always kept an eye on Wharfdale speakers and bought a pair of diamond 200 bookshelf speakers and bi-amped them. Pretty good but, still not the emotional response I was craving. Then, I decided to try a pair of KLH Kendall speakers and hovered over "Buy Now" 10 times or so but, was afraid that I would regret the price if they weren't the "ones". Being an Audio Advice customer, I would watch and read about speaker offerings in their monthly catalogue and the HECO speakers were very intriguing. Still, was nervous about the mounting pile of speakers that I was accumulating to the dismay of my wife.However, Primeday convinced me to pull the trigger on the HECO 700s for a few reasons....In the 70s, all of the killer speakers had paper cones, like the HECOs....I have heard and sold tons of modern speakers made of Kevlar, aluminum and various type of unobtainium...great speakers all...dull sound for me. The specs were next.....crossover points, excellent sensitivity,cabinet construction,well reviewed tweeter, mid range and dual woofers and bi-ampable.They were very easy to put together so I had them up and running in no time. This is the point were most geezers will say they put Steely Dan's "AJA" on but, even tho I love that LP, I started with the latest version of the Beach Boys "Surf Up". As soon as "Feel Flows" began, I knew that I had made the right decision. No break in yet,no system tweeking...I knew. I am currently running an AT 95 shibata cart. Next, I put on a pristine original copy of Dave Brubeck's greatest hits....stunning. My room is about 20 x 30 with 8' ceiling. The speakers are, approximately, 7' apart and about 15" from the wall. Being ported out the back, I get a very pleasant bass response and removed my subwoofer from the system.So....here I am a couple of months later. Cart and speakers well broken in, TT set up as close to perfect as it gets and waking up every morning trying to decide which LP I want to drink my coffee to.IF you are looking for a killer pair of three way floor speakers with outstanding detail, gorgeous looks and unbelievable value, these speakers punch WAY above their weight.....

title: Unitek External M.2 NVMe SATA Adapter - Portable SSD Enclosure Adapter 10Gbps Hard Drive Reader USB C 3.2 Tool Free Pcie Type-C SATA Converter Supports M.2 and 2.5" SATA Solid State Drive
availability: Only 14 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: I've had one of these for about six months and have now bought a second one for my wife's computer.  I've never used the clone function, so can't comment about that.  I use this as a cheap and simple way to connect hard drives to my Mac computer (I initially used this with a Windows 7 computer and it worked with that also).  This does exactly what I want it to do: allow me to use less expensive internal HDDs as external drives with my iMac.  It works with Time Machine (although I've never had to use it to restore a crashed computer, so can't attest to that) and also works as a good external HDD dock.  I prefer this use of internal HDDs rather than made-for-purpose external drives because this allows me to inexpensively keep multiple backups of important files and photos.When I used it with a MacBook Pro, I found that occasionally this would disconnect and I would get prompt that it had "not ejected properly".  This was an annoyance to simply restart the unit, but did not result in any data corruption, as it only lost the connection while the laptop was asleep.  I have not had this problem even once with the iMac, so I assume it has something to do with power-saving options on the laptop.I'm very happy with this thing so far, and "would I buy again" is answered with "yes, I bought a second one for a second family computer.IMPORTANT NOTE:  when placing a brand-new, unformatted HDD into this with iMac, I have found that the new drive must be in the front slot, slot B.  When placed in slot A, the computer will not recognize the drive.  When in slot B, no problem.  Once formatted, it doesn't matter which slot I use, it works just fine.  I assume this has something to do with how this thing is wired for cloning?  At any rate, that's what I've found.

title: Swann 4K Master Security Camera System, 6 Bullet 2 Dome IP Cameras, 8-Ch NVR with 2TB HDD, Indoor/Outdoor PoE Wired, 24/7 Home Surveillance, Color Night Vision, True Detect, Sensor Spotlights
availability: Only 3 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: Nutshell: easy to install and set up, works great, fantastic video and sound quality, solid and sturdy in a metal shell.  I’ve been impressed with the camera’s extended functions and settings which offer the perfect level of customization for my specific situation - custom settings are very easy to set up and tweak.  I really don’t have any major complaints - this camera works and does what it should.Extended:  I added 4K cameras to my existing new-ish Swann POE DVR system which came with 5MP cameras, the increase in video quality with 4K was very apparent.  The 4K cameras also worked better at night and for longer distances.  I’m not a security camera expert, but have some experience with Swann systems, apps, and cameras after using their products over the years and getting them set up right.I’ve read a ton of complaints about all kinds of cameras - a lot have to do with the camera and DVR system not being set up for your specific situation.  Essentially, default settings work ok, but every surveillance scene is unique - tweaking settings will allow the cameras to work better for you.  The Swann systems are easily and intuitively customizable, an important consideration.  I’ve never had issues with their software or DVRs.  If you don’t tweak the settings they WILL give you unwanted alerts - or - not alert when you want them to.My 5 cameras are in very different situations.  3 are on a busy street with lots of traffic, one is indoors, one in my parking lot.  My 4K cameras are on the street, they are set to NOT alert unless somebody enters a very small area near my door, or parks in my driveway - however they capture a wide view around my building and record 24/7.  They have caught every “incident” in perfect 4K detail and crisp focus... faces, license plates, the local graffiti crew, car break ins, etc...  day or night.  I’m not in the best neighborhood, I rely on these cameras to work.  It took a bit to get these cameras to work as I wanted, initially they alerted to everything which was annoying.My indoor camera is almost set to maximum sensitivity and only records when it alerts - but everything sets it off - which is good. It doesn’t record the majority of time with no activity.  I learned I had mice, easily detected in a large room.My parking lot camera is set to “medium” with custom motion zones set up to capture specific areas and alert when anyone comes and goes - the camera does a good job at NOT alerting to tree motion/shadows and small moving animals like rats, birds, or cats - but a dog will set it off.Be aware that 4K cameras will eat up your DVR space fast, especially if recording 24/7.  They also use a lot of bandwidth when streaming from the DVR - extremely fast internet connection required for 4K streaming.  Thankfully the cameras also stream in a lower resolution while still recording in full 4K.  How fast this camera will use your DVR space depends on what frame-rate and resolution you choose for each camera and a bunch of other variables.  My 2TB DVR saves about 6days of video with my 5 cameras and specific configuration.  Before adding the 4K cameras I got about 15 days.This is a POE (power over Ethernet) camera - it’s just a single standard cat5 cable to attach, very simple - the only power plug required is on the connected DVR.  Be aware not all Swann DVRs will be compatible with this POE camera system - in fact, just a few.  The 4K and 5MP cameras I have are great - but if I wanted to add a PTZ camera to this system there is none.  If you want PTZ you need a different Swann camera system.Again, I really don’t have any complaints about this camera after using it for several months - it was a seamless addition to my security system.

categories: ["Office Products","Office & School Supplies","Desk Accessories & Workspace Organizers","Mouse Pads & Wrist Rests","Wrist Rests"]
top_review: I've had this rest for a little over a month now and feel qualified to give my full endorsement to this product.The Good:- The handrest is very comfortable. I find that the lift fits fairly well with my Azio Retro Classic Full Keyboard. As the Retro Classic series can be quite tall compared to standard keyboards, I was impressed that it fit the height. I am on my computer for most of the day, and this rest is just as comfortable as a foam rest. I even like the solid feeling a tad better - not sure why.- Aesthetics are fantastic. The wood has a soft-touch semi-gloss finish that takes on a shine when coming into contact with your hands and the natural oils that emanate from it. It has a wonderfully soft, slightly warm, dark color that fits great with my aesthetic.- Cleaning is a breeze. It really is water-resistant and is easily cleaned with a quick swipe from a microfiber cloth. Compared to my old cloth rest, which seemed to accumulate detritus and debris at a break-neck pace, and required washing every week or two, this rest is amazingly low maintenance.The Bad:- It can chip. I dropped a metal business card holder onto it and it chipped and revealed the pale wood underneath. This was quickly remedied by taking a dark marker and filling the hole in (you can barely tell the difference now) but this is definitely a different experience than the bounce foam pads. This is less of a critique and more of a reminder.The ugly:- When I first received the rest I was totally turned off by the logo in a stark blonde color in the corner of the rest. While it was has grown on me - I wonder if etching the pattern and then staining it might be a better aesthetic option? This is a very small and insignificant gripe that does not effect my enjoyment of this product at all. Why not push a fantastic product to become even better?TLDR;This is a very comfortable rest (Yes, even compared to a foam rest) that is sure to compliment your aesthetics and your carpal tunnel. I wouldn't hesitate to make the switch to this low-maintenance, beautiful handrest this very moment. It is worth the investment.

title: JINTU 14mm F3.5 Ultra Wide Angel Lens Manual Focus Compatible with Sony E Mount Mirrorless Cameras NEX A6000 A6100 A6600 A6400 A6500 A7IV A7II A7III A7RIII ZV-E10 A7RIV A7C
availability: Only 17 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: I think this lens is confused slightly about what it wants to be. The listing talks about (and shows examples of) landscapes and wide angle shots. The front of the lens says "macro" in the second largest font (the first being "CHINA"). While it will focus close (15cm or about 6 inches) I would think of a macro being closer than that.What it is, though, is a pretty decent all manual wide angle prime lens for an APS-C camera. 14mm is a bit wider than my 18-55 kit lens, and it accomplishes a wide view without notable distortion. Something like 98% of the focus travel is spent between 0.15m and 1m, with just a tiny bit left to go from 1m to infinity. What this means in real life is that for anything over about 2m away, your essentially at infinity. So all those landscape shots are actually fairly easy because it's just infinity.At closer range you do have to focus, and that means finding what works as far as focus aids on your camera and taking the time to do it. But I found just playing around that it was relatively easy to throw on focus peaking and quickly approximate focus. Is it going to get me into National Geographic? No. Is it fun? Yep.Aperture range is okay. f/3.5-16 means you can open up for some blurring against close up subjects, and you can stop down to keep detail. It's not super fast but it's not super expensive.The construction feels very solid. It's definitely a chunk. It's weighty and all metal, including the permanent sunshade. Aperture and focus rings rotate smoothly and with even resistance throughout their range of travel. They both have pleasantly knurled grip surfaces that are easy to engage. It looks decent on the camera and engages with the E mount like every other lens I have.The lens is also packaged well with a nice neoprene case and caps for both ends. The case can clip onto my other bag which is a bonus."Real" lenses are shockingly expensive. If you're in the market for that, you're not looking at a $150 piece of manual glass. But for hobbyists or someone who wants to work with a manual lens, this isn't a bad wide angle prime lens that won't break the bank.

title: Portable AM/FM Radio, Small Pocket Radio with Bass Speaker, Support Micro SD Card and Record, Long Battery Life, Alarm and Sleep Function
top_review: This AM/FM Radio/Mp3 Player & Recorder is very impressive for its small size and low cost.I was looking for a small battery powered AM/FM radio to listen to Talk Radio on my tractor while mowing fields. Even though the audio quality through its internal speaker is impressive for its size, I plan to use wired headsets which makes it sound even better.The built-in Mp3 Player, which can also be used to record voice or radio, is a plus for me since I ocassionally will want to record some of what I hear for playback to my wife later. And the recorded Mp3 audio file is better quality than what comes from the speaker when played back on a better sound system. However, you must install your own 32GB max Micro SD card for the record function to work.Another unit that I purchased and returned for this one, was more expensive, the display was hard to see in sunlight unlike this backlit LCD display, and was subject to noise interferrence even on the FM band, which I have not had on this unit.  It also had no internal speaker, just a headset jack which must be used for radio reception since the headset cord becomes the antenna.This uint has its own built-in telescopic antenna for the FM band and an internal Magnetic internal antenna for the AM band so the FM antenna can stay retracted when using AM.Both the AM and FM reception sensitivity is as good or better than the radio in my new 2024 truck. It also has a built-in digital clock which be handy on the tractor since I don't carry my smartphone on the tractor for fear of dirt, dust, vibration and rain damage.It came with very detailed (real English) accurate instructions and the keypad controls are very user friendly with just a little practice.It has a USB Type C charging port which is compatible with all of my newer battery chargers. Even though it comes with a USB-A to USB-C charging cable, you have to supply the 5Vdc charging cube.At this point, I have not used it enough to know if the battery does indeed last 20 hours as advertised.But I will not be suprised if it does and perhaps even longer while using headsets.The only dissappointment was that the included Bluetooth 5.0 feature acts only as a receiver so that you can broadcast from your phone to this unit but not a transmitter to connect to wireless earbuds, which it states clearly in the product description.Basically, it does everything the ad purports and I highly recommend it as a good and safe purchase for the money.

top_review: Here's the thing, I wanted a charging dock for my Xbox Series X controllers. So, I did what any person does nowadays, I searched for reviews... and then I searched for more reviews and then more. Spoiler, reviews were shockingly limited unhelpful. So, here is a helpful review.1. quality - this charger feels solid and is easy to use; the controller fits on the dock easily, doesn't feel unstable or tippy. The led "breathes" to let you know it's charging and turns solid once charged. I've never struggled to connect the controller properly or fumbled with putting them on.2. charging time - I haven't timed it (sorry?) but it's fast and you can charge both at once or only one at a time.3. battery life - hours...  I can't say more or I'll sound even less like I have a life than I do now, but it's hours.4. battery covers - it comes with two one for the X and one for the Series X. They fit perfectly and they even look good on the blue controllers. The gap in the cover for the connection to the dock isn't too much. It's not too ugly and it doesn't interfere with use or plugging the controller in by usb-c.5. usb - here's my biggest complaint, the plug for the dock is not usb, so you must use the cable it comes with, you can't use another cable and have to have a wall plug nearby. It was fine for me, but if you're out of room on your power strip, you have my sympathies.6. battery - this one has the largest battery that I could find out of all the charging docks, so that's a plus.7. licensed - it's officially approved by Xbox, so I don't have to worry about it killing my $60 controllers.8. size - it's not tiny, but it doesn't take up unnecessary space, it isn't too tall or too long, pretty much perfect for storing / charging 2 controllers.9. color - it only comes in black, which is fine because it matches my Xbox, but if you wanted it in white or to match your controller, it's not going to happen.This is the charging dock to buy if you want to charge 2 controllers. It's easy to use, has a good battery life, doesn't take up too much space, quick charging, and looks cool. I appreciate the peace of mind of knowing Xbox was ok with it and the fact that I can store my controllers on it and not worry about where they are or if they've been charged lately.

title: SABRENT USB 3.0 to SATA Dual Bay External Hard Drive Docking Station for 2.5 or 3.5in HDD, SSD with Hard Drive Duplicator/Cloner Function [22TB Support] (EC-DSK2)
categories: ["Electronics","Computers & Accessories","Computer Accessories & Peripherals","Hard Drive Accessories","Docking Stations"]
top_review: I ordered the following:SABRENT USB 3.1 to SATA External Hard Drive Docking Station for 2.5 or 3.5in HDD, SSD [Includes Both Type C and Type A Cables Supports UASP and 20TB Drives] (DS-UTC1)The reason why is because I wanted the option to connect to either a USB type A or type C port.Things I couldn't figure out before the purchase which I can now confirm are as follows.- The unit has no plugs on the front. What appears to be a plug on the front is a light.- On the back, the unit has 2 plugs. One for the proprietary power cord (standard nipple - looks like it could be easily replaced if needed). One for the USB connection which is indeed a USB C port. This is important to me since in some of the product pics, it looked like the USB connection was proprietary. It's not. It's a good ol' USB C port which means I can use any appropriate cable.I use this device across computers - mainly mac and windows, and sometimes unix variants. Worked great on a mac running latest OS as of Jan 3 2022. I assume it would work on windows. I partially assume the same for unix vars but don't take my word for it. These days, most OSs support USB mass storage devices.I have 2 old 2 TB SATA drives which were both in a RAID0 config in another device. I didn't care about the data on them. Goal was to resurrect them and use them for storage and then once loaded, put the drives in a safe and forget about them.Plugged them in and my mac said it couldn't read it. No problem. In disk utility, I could see the mount. I picked erase, exfat, MBR - and in about 10 seconds the drive was ready to use. This is exactly what I needed.Again, I was not concerned about keeping the data on the drives. In a scenario where you might be, I would expect the drive to properly mount and be readable assuming it has an appropriate file system / MBR loaded on it.I love how the device is small, light, and I can tote it in a backpack.An approximate $25 solution that now unlocks the use of many hard drives. I view this as an excellent cost to value scenario.Very happy with purchase.

title: NEBULA by Anker Mars II Pro 500 ANSI Lumen Portable Projector, Native 720P, 40-100 Inch Image TV Projector, Movie Projector with WiFi and Bluetooth, 3Hr Video Playtime, Watch Anywhere
top_review: We bought this to do backyard movies and television. We live in a garden home neighborhood, which means we're close to our neighbors and their lights and have plenty of streetlights and other light pollution. Even with all that, once the sun sets, this projector does a fabulous job. We often have the fire pit going or the lights on in the gazebo, and there's still a great clear picture. The only time you really need a truly dark environment is with shows or movies that have a very dark ambience-- for some episodes of the Mandalorian, for example, we needed to kill the gazebo lights to see it well.  Finding Nemo did not need such considerations. We do typically run the projector in the brighter mode since we have the ability to run power to it in our backyard. We have tested it on battery power and got about 2 hours of viewing. Even on battery power, there's plenty of brightness in the picture if you're using it after dark.I highly recommend setting up all your accounts in the projector ahead of time. It makes it SO much easier to deal with logging into all the accounts and typing in your passwords if you're just shining it on the wall in your living room the night before movie night instead of trying to set everything up while everyone stares at you! Some of those apps are a pain to navigate, and there's a bit of a learning curve to using the remote and/or phone app. You get used to it, but it takes a minute.Our setup:We project onto a projector screen (just the 100" Amazon Basic one)-- we attached projector screen mounting brackets with to our house under the eaves and attached a set of carabiners rated for 75 pounds (extreme overkill) on each end of the projector screen. My husband can pull the screen out from the storage closet and clip the it onto the hooks in the mounting brackets in less than a minute. We have a set of ground anchors near the wall, and we use two bungee cords (I used a pair of pliers to widen the hooks a bit) so that they loop around the bottom ends of the projector screen and then connect to the anchors. They're long enough that they only have a tiny bit of tension on the screen-- just enough to keep the screen from blowing, twisting, and kinking if there's a breeze.When we're not using the screen, we disconnect the bungees and roll it up, where it's safely tucked away under the eaves. We leave it up during good weather but can easily unhook it and put it away if rain threatens.We paired our projector with a cheap tripod from Walmart and a couple orange traffic cones from Home Depot so that the kids don't run into the tripod in the dark. Like some others have commented, the tripod mounting hole is a little shallow, so it can make the projector feel unstable on a tripod mount. Thanks to those commenters, I anticipated having the same problem and was armed with supplies to solve it. We bought a couple neoprene washers from Home Depot and placed them between the projector and the tripod mount. That made it a snug fit and eliminated any wobble. We leave the tripod mount attached all the time and just store the whole unit in its bag. (It does NOT come with any kind of storage bag, by the way-- we ordered the Anker one off Amazon because I disliked having to put it back in the cardboard box each time we used it.)We often sit back a good ways from the projector, and while the built-in sound is fine for me, my husband is kind of hard of hearing. We pair the projector via Bluetooth with an Anker Soundcore Flare 2 speaker we already owned and sit the speaker right next to us. They play together fabulously. There's no sound lag at all, at least none I can discern. We did discover that it helps to turn the speaker on a few seconds before turning the projector on. They pair quicker and more easily when the speaker is turned on first. And as we already have an actual bluetooth speaker, we've never really tried to use our projector as a bluetooth speaker. The Soundcore Flare 2 is a lot cheaper and more durable if my kids get a little too crazy with their elementary dance parties.We've had this thing for going on three months and love it. I did a lot of research and agonized over which portable projector to buy, and I'm really happy with the choice I made for my family. If that changes, I'll update this review, but I don't suspect I'll need to.

title: 10Gtek 10Gb SFP+ RJ45 Copper Transceiver Module 10GBase-T SFP+ Compatible with Cisco SFP-10G-T-S, Ubiquiti UF-RJ45-10G, Mikrotik S+RJ10, Netgear, TP-Link, D-Link
top_review: 📍 Le produit : Très bon produit mais franchement, le prix est incroyablement cher. La technologie fibre se démocratisant de plus en plus, je ne trouve pas ça normal d'avoir encore des tarifs comme celui-ci et surtout pour un simple adaptateur SFP/RJ45. Sinon, l'emballage est beau et n'essayez pas de l'ouvrir de force, il se coulisse tout simplement vers la droite et vous aurez enfin accès au précieux sésame.💻 Fonctionnement : Actuellement, il est branché au port "F" de la Freebox Delta et cela fonctionne à merveille. Malheureusement, j'ai actuellement un câble Ethernet de catégorie 6 bridé à 1 Gbps et on peut voir sur la photo envoyée que le câble rempli quand même très bien sa fonction première et dépasse même légèrement ses brides. Je reçois normalement un câble RJ45 de catégorie 7 qui lui est bridé à 10 Gbps mais, ma carte mère elle, est bridée à 2,5 Gbps. En toute logique, le débit devrait quand même augmenter légèrement. J'attends cependant une carte réseau complémentaire (qui sera branchée sur un slot x16) pour profiter pleinement des 10 Gbps que peut offrir la Freebox Delta. Dites vous également que ce produit est relié à un câble CAT 6 bridé à 1 Gbps de 40 mètres (avec un peu de rabe) donc autant dire qu'avec un câble plus court, les résultats peuvent être légèrement meilleurs. Pensez également à bien enlever toute la poussière du port "F" de la Freebox Delta avant de le brancher histoire que votre débit ne soit pas perturbé. D'autre part, effectivement, sa température de fonctionnement est énorme, l'adaptateur devient très rapidement très chaud, pensez y si jamais vous voulez le retirer.🎁 Conclusion : Produit qui fait son travail mais malheureusement bridé par ma configuration actuelle. Je modifierai mon avis lorsque toutes les brides auront été enlevées et que sa pleine capacité pourra s'exprimer. Malgré ça, je recommande vivement son achat si votre configuration le permet ou si vous comptez comme moi, modifier votre configuration plus tard.

title: Nylavee Computer Speakers, PC Sound bar for Desktop, HiFi Stereo Soundbar, Large Speaker Drivers, 3.5mm Aux-in Connection, USB Powered Mini Speaker Soundbar for Desktop Monitor, PC, Laptop, Tablets
categories: ["Electronics","Computers & Accessories","Computer Accessories & Peripherals","Audio & Video Accessories","Computer Speakers"]
top_review: Nice "fit and finish." Feels heavy enough to be good quality. The all-in-one volume knob is intuitive and seems to work well, and ample instructions are provided for bluetooth connection etc. The soundbar is photographed here below a large 32" monitor.I did have a bit of a problem connecting to my computer's aux output (3.55mm jack), but a restart fixed that problem so it seems that issue was on the PC end of things. Once up and running, the sound was just ok at first. I messed around with the available settings in Windows and determined the following:The plug-and-play setting defaulted to "enable audio enhancements," which I guess means on-board signal processing in the soundbar itself. With this setting enabled, the sound is very smooth and pleasing, except way too boomy in the low range (less than ~150hz or so). However, without the audio enhancement enabled, the sound was thin / poor. This prompted me to look further for EQ settings, but...My audio driver does not have support for equalization (boo).I did install a Chrome extension to test the effects of EQ. Sure enough, just a small reduction of the low end and boost in the high end made the sound real nice. Still pretty "small" sound, but pretty darn good for the size of the soundbar....So, I'd say it's pretty good for small speakers, and for the price. Definitely better than both the built-in laptop speakers and also way better than the built-in monitor speakers, which this is replacing. If this was a high-end device, I'd *want* the onboard "enhancements" to be perfect out of the box, but I don't know if that would be reasonable to expect either since there are many variables between the PC and docking station. If this cost $100, I'd probably consider giving it 4 stars just because it seems good (very good, even), but not amazing, and also required a bit of modification at least for my setup. But for the price, this device seems to work very well. Even better if you have the ability to apply a bit of EQ!
