top_review: I sometimes drive for ride share companies, and like to hang out at the airport, which tends to be longer trips, so I wanted this monitor/tablet for my backseat passengers.The monitor comes packaged with two power cords; a 12v socket vehicle cord, and a standard 110v home cord, as well as an HDMI cable.  The monitor does not have an internal battery, so you will need to use one of the power cords with it at all times.  Additionally, this monitor includes a mount for your front seat headrests, so it can be mounted in the car, which also doubles as a stand when using it on a flat surface.This monitor does have multiple functions and ways of using it.  First, it can be used a tablet, where you can connect it to WiFi and download different apps and/or games from the Google Play store.  It can also be used with a flash card or thumb drive, allowing you to play stored movies and music, or transfer media from a flash card or thumb drive to the onboard storage, which is 32GB.  You can also connect other devices to the monitor via the HDMI in port, such as a gaming console, tablet, phone, etc., or you can connect the monitor to another device, such as a TV, via the HDMI out port, allowing you to use this as a streaming device for a larger display.  Additionally, the device does allow screen mirroring, allowing you to cast your device to it.When using the device in the car, it does have speakers built in, but also includes a built-in FM transmitter, which allows you to transmit the audio from the monitor to your vehicle's stereo system.  Otherwise, you can connect wireless headsets to the device, or use the standard 3.5mm headset jack as well.The screen quality is decent, and is nice and vibrant, although it's not the best when it has direct sunlight hitting it, for which I may try to find a screen protector that also remedies the glare from the sun.  The touch screen seems to be decently responsive.At a price point of regularly $328.00, or $309 while on sale currently, the price is quite high, even considering how versatile it is.  I do feel like this device should be priced more in the $150 range.Overall, I'm very pleased with this product, and may order a second one for the other side of my car, if and when the price comes down considerably.

title: Soyuz Microphones Launcher - Analog In-Line Microphone Preamp and Activator for Dynamic and Ribbon Mics
availability: Only 1 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: Much like the Cloudlifter or FetHead, this device uses phantom power to increase the gain of your microphone (26db in this case).  This is especially useful for quieter mics like Ribbon microphones and some Dynamic mics.  Does it do well at this task?  Yes, very much so.  In fact, with my MXL R144, I can turn down the gain a bit more than when I use the Cloudlifter.  But, this also does a little more.  The Cloudlifter and other similar products try to be" transparent" and not change anything about the sound, save for the gain levels.  The Launcher imparts a bit of color and warmth.  It's very subtle, but it gently smooths the sound.  A gentle rolling off of the high end using physical components rather than EQ settings or software.  I suggest finding detailed reviews on Youtube so you can hear what it does.  Listen carefully, because it is subtle.  I think it makes the sound just a little more pleasing and a tad more "vintage."As for build quality, this thing is built like a tank.  The outer metal shell is thicker than that of the Cloudlifter (which is built well to begin with).  The unit comes with a zipper pouch for storage and travel and quality assurance cards signed by the men who built and inspected the unit, a nice touch.Should you buy it?  Well, it comes down to whether or not you need the gain booting abilities AND want the subtle changes it makes to the sound.  This will use phantom power and not pass it on, so any mic that needs it cannot use with without some extra power source in the chain after it.  For me, I need the boost to gain and I love warmer, more vintage sounds.  If you want more gain and no color, you will be very happy with the Cloudlifter.

title: Skinomi Full Body Skin TechSkin Protector for Nintendo 3DS XL (2012, 1st Generation) (Screen Protector + Back Cover) HD Film
top_review: As the title states, you absolutely must have patience when applying this skin to your system.  Set aside some time for yourself when you've nothing else to do, put on a show or movie in the background, and apply the skin very carefully.If you watch the video, it is very helpful in figuring out how to properly adhere the skin to your system.  I managed to make the bottle of application liquid last the whole time, and I have a sliver of the liquid left.  Use it sparingly, but don't be stingy--and if you run out, just put some water in the bottle and shake it as the instructions say.  DO NOT spray it directly onto your device, and be careful of how much you apply to the sticky side of the skin, as you will have to squeegee it out and it can leak into your device in the wrong place.  You only need a thin layer, and you don't want any liquid getting into the crevices of your expensive 3DS.  Also, don't get your hands too wet with it, but don't let them be totally dry either.Make sure your system is clean, the way the video shows you, or fingerprints, grime, and fuzz will be present under the skin and it won't look very attractive.My experience with applying the Skinomi skin was time-consuming and a bit tedious, but with patience, I managed to get all the pieces on perfectly.  There are no labels on the parts of the skin, but it's honestly not difficult to figure out.  It's rather like a very simple puzzle.  I had to hold down the edges on the outside portion of the skin because they didn't want to adhere to the curves of my 3DS, but I just held my hands over the edges for a minute or two, and they didn't come up again.  I did the screen pieces first, since those were the ones I was most likely to screw up, but the sheets actually fit very well, and the liquid makes it easy to adjust them to be perfectly aligned.  The only pieces that weren't perfect were the edges of the bottom portion, along the edge where the headphone jack and the power light is.  They were a bit too long, so they overlap in the center, but it's not noticeable at all unless I'm staring at it closely.One more tip: when you're using the little card to get the liquid out from under the skin, you can hold the microfiber cloth at the edge to catch any liquid so it doesn't drip down and get into anything.  It helped me, especially with my screens.I applied the skin roughly five days ago, and all the little microbubbles have worked themselves out.  Now my 3DS is pristine and lovely, and it's protected from scratch damage.  I feel much better about using it, especially now that I know my touch screen won't get marred by the stylus.

title: Arsvita Car Audio Cassette to Aux Adapter, 5.0 Bluetooth Receiver Kit for Cassette to Aux Adapter, Bluetooth Receiver Compatible with 3.5 MM Auxillary Cable Tape Adapter, Black
categories: ["Electronics","Car & Vehicle Electronics","Vehicle Electronics Accessories","Audio & Video Accessories","Bluetooth Car Kits"]
top_review: I have a wired version of this cassette adaptor from the same company and it works fine. I wanted a bluetooth version for my older car. It technically still has a wire sticking out, but it does not have to mechanically attach to my phone. The bonus about that is, if the bluetooth dongle battery dies I can still plug the wire into my phone anyway. I also like that the bluetooth dongle can be adapted to other devices with a 3.5 mm jack. There is another model of this cassette adaptor where the dongle cannot be detached from the cassette.It works great. I haven't used up all of the battery life on it, so perhaps I have spoken too soon. But it sounds better than cheaper versions where I would need to eject the tape several times to get it to line up just right with the play heads to get stereo and the best sound. The play head on this one looks better and is aligned properly. I have been trying a lot of the cheaper versions of a bluetooth adaptor and saw some of them had the tape head askew, making it difficult to get the correct alignment with the player in the car stereo. With the cheaper ones I could hear the "tape" gears turning very quietly, but still noticeable. Those cheaper versions made loud scraping and grinding noises as the gears rotated in the car tape deck. I bought one (probably all the same product with different labeling), where the reviews suggested opening the 6 tiny screws and removing some magic combination of gears that would eliminate the noise but still fool the cassette deck into believing it is a real cassette tape and not eject it or flip from side to side continuously. I opened that tape half a dozen times and could not find the correct combination of gears to leave or remove. The $16 tape ended up in the trash. I noticed it was a little thicker than this one because the bluetooth unit was inside the deck.

title: Mediabridge ULTRA Series Subwoofer Cable (25 Feet) - Dual Shielded with Gold Plated RCA to RCA Connectors - Black
top_review: I like Mediabridge products.  Quality feel and function, no cheap feel, nice ends, yet doesn't break the bank.  Their banana plug ends are sweet!!!  Cables fully functional and I have no complaints, in this price range, or the sonic capacity of their hooks in this price range.Yes, to a point of diminishing return, better cables/hooks can allow the transfer of better signals but you spend mightily for that small incremental increase in realized, audible audio improvement.  I have some of those hooks and they sound good.  But they cannot make the sound BETTER than the source.  Mine are hooked to $10,000 McIntosh components, and no the Mediabridge cannot compare.  But you can afford the Mediabridge and still have quality likely higher than the big box stores sell that claim to be Best.Best I can tell they use all copper wire.  This is good cause some don't, including some speaker wire so beware.  You don't want that stuff.  Higher impedance and greater signal loss.  No thanks.  Real copper and OFC is the only way to go.  (Unless you can afford silver wire.)You think you can hear a BIG difference between $300 hooks compared to these, and have the disposable cash, then buy those.  Be happy.  Sleep good.  Some CAN hear the difference, me one of them.  A lot depends on your speakers there, too.  :)Want to transfer a quality signal on a budget, try Mediabridge products.  This is their niche.  I like em and my main system is McIntosh.  I use different cables for that, but the cost is waaaaaaay different.

top_review: We recently bought a minivan equipped with an HDMI port to connect to the dropdown TV. To make road trips more enjoyable for the kids, I initially purchased an Apple adapter for our iPad. When that adapter broke, I opted for a 10-foot HDMI cable, eliminating the need for an adapter altogether. This review covers my experience with the new HDMI cable.Setup and Use:The HDMI cable setup was incredibly simple. Without needing an adapter, it directly connects the iPad to the minivan's TV. The 10-foot length is perfect, allowing the cable to reach from the back of the van to the front passenger seat, where we can easily control the iPad. Additionally, iPhones with a USB-C connector can also connect seamlessly, offering versatility with our devices.Features:- Adapter-Free Connection: The direct HDMI connection eliminates the need for additional adapters, reducing clutter.- Long Reach: The 10-foot cable allows easy access from the back to the front seat, providing convenience in controlling the iPad or iPhone.- Durable Build: The cable is made of high-quality, durable material, capable of withstanding being stepped on and twisted as people get in and out of the van.Performance:- Ease of Use: Setting up and using the cable is straightforward, making it simple to find and play content for the kids without dealing with a stack of DVDs.- Signal Quality: There is no signal interference, even when the cable moves around. The connections on both ends are strong and secure, preventing accidental disconnections.- Durability: The cable's robust construction ensures it can handle the rigors of constant use in a minivan environment without breaking or fraying.Conclusion:Switching to this HDMI cable has made in-car entertainment much more manageable and enjoyable. It simplifies the process of finding and playing content for the kids and reduces the need to carry a bunch of DVDs. The cable's durability and reliable performance make it an excellent investment for any minivan equipped with an HDMI port. Overall, I'm extremely satisfied with this purchase and highly recommend it for anyone looking to streamline their in-car entertainment setup.

I knew I needed a better grip so, even though I plan on getting the battery/vertical grip down the road, I also wanted the option of a non-battery version.  So....This.Good choice. It really makes a difference.  If I use the X-T3 as a travel camera, I'll probably leave the battery/vertical grip at home and just take this one, since it doesn't bulk up the camera that much.

Il convient à tous sauf ceux qui veulent un nouveau design un écran plus grand, de l’usb c et plus de puissance pour faire du montage ou autres qui demande énormément de ressources.La puce A13 reste très puissante donc avec les mises  à jour d’Apple il tiendra longtemps et elle est capable de faire énormément de choses. Pour atteindre les limites c’est compliqué de nos jours tellement les puces sont trop puissantes pour l’utilisation qu’on en fait.Le stockage 256 go est bien plus confortable si vous installer des jeux et stocker beaucoup de choses dessus puis il faut du stockage si vous voulez le conserver longtemps sans être embêter. Car le 64 go reste juste en 2022 à part si vous stocker dans le cloud et que vous installer pas des jeux ou apps volumineuses car ça se remplit vite; avec les apps qui pèsent plus qu’avant mais pour la plupart des gens ça convient pour une tablette.Pour regarder du contenu l’écran est très bien calibré et de qualité. L’écran n’est pas laminé tout comme sur le 10 mais c’est pas si grave. Il y a des reflets mais ça va. La luminosité est au même niveau que la gamme sauf les iPad pro qui sont plus lumineux.Le son est très bon même si on aurait préféré un peu plus de basses, il sort que d’un côté on s’y fait mais si vous voulez du spatial audio prenez vos AirPods pour plus d’immersion pour films ou séries.Niveau caméra arrière c’est du 8mpx mais pas très grave, personnes prend des photos avec un iPad mais la caméra avant 12mpx avec cadre centré pour les appels vidéos est de bonne qualité comme sur toute la gamme.A 559€ le prix d’avant pour 256 go c’est un bon choix mais au nouveau prix de 639€ c’est beaucoup trop cher pour ce qu’il offre si vous le trouvez au alentour de 500€ c’est mieux. title: Retocolor Emoticon 400 35mm Disposable Film Camera 27EXP, ISO400, Color Negative Film, Focus Free, Easy to Use, Built in Flash, Single Use (Film and Battery Included)
top_review: Okay, first things first, it's a pretty good build quality, honestly. I grew up with disposable cameras, so when I got this, the first thing I asked myself was "were they always this heavy?" My little sister is a huge, HUGE fan of anything Japanese, and she's been bugging me relentlessly to help her get into film photography. This was the perfect gift. Just seeing the package made her excited.So onto the meat: The film itself is ISO 400, which is a good middle ground for almost any occasion. Decent on cloudy days, decent indoors (using the flash), it's a disposable camera, you know what it looks like.The directions on the camera explain how to use it very well, showing the distance between subjects that you're wanting to take pictures of, it's all very easy to explain and understand.Development: It's standard C-41, so virtually ANY film lab can process it. Often times, off brand cameras tend to use ECN-2 (old motion picture film, usually) because it's cheap for them to purchase in bulk, and that can't be processed at a C-41 lab, so this makes this camera, already, an even better entry point for new photographers.Quality: Well, looking at how her photos came out, it looks to me like whatever film is inside of this, it's most likely re-branded Fujifilm, so expect cooler colors. Yellows and brows appear a little more muted, while greens and blues tend to pop more. The little hearts and letters are a great, fun addition to the pictures themselves. While not exactly my style, I'm not a 16 year old girl, either, so I'm just happy she's happy.Overall, the camera seriously worked well. The flash is a hold button style, so press it down, take a picture, and release the button. Simple design, good execution, and fun to use. That's all that really matters.If they ever make a little point and shoot that looks like this one, I'll have to pick it up. She was devastated when I told her that the film lab can't give her the camera back when she's done with it.

title: DJI Mini 3 Pro (DJI RC), Mini Drone with 4K Video, 48MP Photo, 34 Mins Flight Time, Less than 249 g, Obstacle Sensing, Return to Home, FAA Remote ID Compliant, Drone with Camera for Adults
availability: Only 4 left in stock - order soon.
categories: ["Toys & Games","Remote & App Controlled Vehicles & Parts","Quadcopters & Multirotors"]
top_review: TL;DR: This is my second experience with DJI drones (first was a Phantom 2 Vision when droning was a new thing). This drone is awesome for beginners and experienced drone flyers. Camera is beautiful and functional. The RC unit is awesome. The range is great. The battery life is OK. Just hold your nose and buy the "fly more" battery combo you can get on top of this. I ended up buying almost everything separately eventually anyway and paid more for it. If you're on the fence, go for it. This drone will do it all.PROS: Got a great discount as a Prime Day deal. Shipping was super fast. Drone comes packaged great. You have to create a DJI account before you can fly. The controls are incredibly intuitive and easy to learn. It still amazes me how you can just sit the controller down and the drone holds its place in space perfectly. The drone weighs under 250g so no FAA registration is required. I'm a video pro and a media junkie and I will say the camera is just awesome--beautiful video and photos. Range is great, I can get about 4,000 feet away in hilly Western Pennsylvania before I start losing range at about 375 feet up. The remote control with the screen is such an upgrade over the old Phantom series controllers. I helped my neighbor locate missing cows by putting the drone up and you could clearly see the brown and black cows on the screen from over 300 feet up. I really love this drone. I've had it about two months and I've flown it almost 30 hours already, which is more than I flew in the entire life of my Phantom drone. Everything is USB-C, which is awesome. The RC unit charges with it, the drone plugs in and charges with it, the triple charger (sold separately) uses it. The features that are built in are incredible. The smart tracking and circling features are great. The crash avoidance hardware is amazing and will save your drone a nasty crash. You can control that stuff and turn it off if you're operating in close quarters though, which is great.CONS: I didn't initially buy a MicroSD card with it and you can only record about 2 minutes of video on the hard drive, but that's my fault. Make sure you check with DJI's compatibility list for which SD cards are approved to use. You don't want corrupted data from junk cards. It doesn't come with any built-in 3 mile strobe light "required" by the FAA for flying at night. The batteries say they'll do 30 minutes, but I usually get about 20-25 before I have to put it down. Pro and Con: The drone knows where you are allowed to be and where you aren't (around airports, government buildings, etc) and will prompt you or downright stop you from flying in these areas.TIPS: Buy the "fly more" combo. I initially skipped on it because I didn't want to pay that steep price, but I ended up buying almost everything that comes in the kit anyway. You will want at least 3 batteries, a charger unit, a case, and ND filters, at a minimum. Do some research on FAA drone regulations and make yourself familiar with them. I am learning more the longer I own the thing. People are amazed at the beautiful, smooth shots I come back with. I'm a video pro so my standards are super high. Drone tech has finally caught up with my high expectations and THIS DRONE IS AWESOME. Absolute 5-star product!!

title: Keyboard Case for iPad Air 11-inch (M2) 2024 & iPad Pro 11 inch (1st/2nd/3rd/4th Generation) – Magic-Style Magnetic Keyboard Case with Multi-Touch Trackpad Compatible with 10.9” iPad Air 4th/5th Gen.
top_review: I got an iPad as a gift, but I have not been utilizing it as much as I'd like to. I decided the best thing I could do was get a keyboard case and take it with me on the go in place of a computer. While the Apple Magic Keyboard looks incredible and I'm sure is worth the price, I am not really in a position to drop $300 on a keyboard case at this moment and was looking for something more cost effective. I've only had this keyboard case for a couple of days, so keep that in mind, but so far I am really loving it!My iPad Air fits perfectly in it and the magnets holding the iPad in place feel strong, I have zero concern about that. Everything seems very stable, well thought out, and sturdy. It's very sleek and does not take up much room in my purse at all. I had no issues with the initial pairing and every time I open it up, it's immediately connected. No issues with that so far. I think there is a learning curve with the keyboard features and shortcuts, but I am figuring it out and enjoying everything so far. I love that I can keep the backlight off of the keyboard so it doesn't drain the battery, but turn it on and control the brightness when necessary. It's also very easy to change the trackpad setting so a tap registers as a click. I was a bit annoyed having to physically press down to click, especially coming from laptops where you tap the trackpad to click. But the case actually came with a FAQ sheet that explains how to do it, and it includes a handy chart of keyboard shortcuts which is helping me get used to it. Typing on the keyboard itself has been fine, it is smaller than my computer and work laptop keyboards (naturally), but it also doesn't feel too jarring transitioning to the smaller keyboard.The keyboard case itself must be charged separately from the iPad, it does not charge the iPad with the pass through charging, which I believe the Apple Magic Keyboard does. For me this is not an issue at all, I don't really mind charging them separately and both the keyboard and the iPad use the same charging cable. I can't comment on how the battery life is so far, but I can update my review after a few months of use. So far, I fully charged it and have spent some time off and on using it, but the iPad shows a completely full charge still. Judging from other reviews, it seems like battery life is long and will be fine for what I need.I'll be honest, for the price I am really happy and incredibly impressed with this. I was making this purchase with the intention of eventually upgrading to the Apple keyboard. But now I'm not so sure I would even want to upgrade, I really do like this and it's $200 cheaper than the Apple keyboard. Yes, you sacrifice some features as a result, but honestly none of them seem all that huge. And since I've never used the Apple Magic Keyboard, those couple of features that I am missing seem negligible to me at this point. It definitely seems worth the money I paid and I'm very satisfied!Edit 9/21/23 - I’ve been using this case since mid July and I’m still satisfied and have had no issues! title: WiFi Extender, 1200Mbps Dual Band 2.4G/5G Wireless Internet Repeater and Signal Amplifier, WiFi Extender Signal Booster for Home, Wireless Internet Extender, Long Range Amplifier with Ethernet Port
top_review: With my initial setup, I didn't think it was doing much.  I'm using it to extend my network to a Blink camera 3 brick walls away from my router.  It seemed to help a little, but then the camera still kept losing signal.  I eventually realized that the extender was extending the wifi signal, but the Blink camera was not seeing it.  This was because the extender creates its own network with "_Pro" added to the base network name.  Blink is looking to the base network name.  I eventually learned I could just reset the extender, set it up using the manual approach (not WPS), and in that process make the extender network name match the base network.  Now, it works great.  (I also learned an alternative is to have another Sync module and steer it to the extender's network, but would result in having >1 "home" on the home page to see the cameras one the first and then second sync modules)

title: Amcrest 5Series 4K POE NVR 8CH 4K/6MP/5MP/4MP/3MP/1080P Network Video Recorder (8-Port PoE) - Supports up to 8 x 4K IP Cameras, Supports up to 2 x 10TB Hard Drives (Not Included)
availability: Only 1 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: Generally, I am not a fan of Amcrest and hope I never have to engage with their support. I do have some experience with it. However, the value of this NVR outweighed that concern. The system is easy to setup and configure generally. It is not as intuitive as an Apple device but it is not overly complex once you understand how to use the software. This device has been running stable for me for 2 months now with 5 of 8 cameras connected, 2 being WiFi. I have cameras from Dahua, Hikvision, and Amcrest connected to the NVR. The user interface is responsive, it works with a variety of cameras, it has been stable and reliable, and it is priced at a good value relative to other options on the market. I am not using the build in switch with DHCP server but have tested it and it works as expected, recognized the cameras and really makes setting up your IP camera network so much easier. The only complaint I would identify so far is that the exhaust fan on the unit is loud which may be a positive if you enjoy white noise.I have a 4MP, 3x3MP, and a 720p camera connected at max quality settings and the NVR sees 50-60 Mb/s of ingress traffic with none-to-light motion in the camera frames. I have not noticed an issue with this NVR from a traffic or processing standpoint in this configuration other than there is a slight ~1-2 second delay between live and on-screen display.

I followed my usual routine for applying a screen protector (which prevents bubbles or dust becoming trapped between the protector and the screen).  I took my laptop and the protector into a highly humidified room (removes dust particles in the air).  I cleaned the laptop screen and placed the protector against it, removing the adhesive strips.  This did not work well since there was moisture trapped between the screen and the protector.  Thankfully, the protector is designed to be removable.  I turned off the humidifier and waited a few minutes.  I removed the protector and dried off the laptop and the protector screens. Then I placed the protector back on the laptop screen.  It worked perfectly!  No air bubbles or dust trapped beneath the protector.I love that it blocks blue light.  I am very sensitive to blue light which causes insomnia.Since it is removable and can be cleaned as needed, I expect it to last much longer than the standard  screen protectors.  Very happy with this product.  Well designed, game changing product.  Bargain priced at $19.99.

title: LG RCT689H Combi Recorder Tuner TNT USB
categories: ["Electronics","Home Cinema, TV & Video","DVD Players & Recorders","DVD Recorders"]
top_review: remarque préliminaire : appareil utilisé pour recopier de vieilles cassettes, ou pour graver des DVD à partir d'enregistrements faits sur le disque dur d'un décodeur satellite numérique. J'avais acheté un Toshiba pour ces fonctions, mais après trois pannes de lecture du magnétoscope en deux mois, Amazon a bien voulu me reprendre cet appareil. Indépendamment de cela, j'avais trouvé le mode d'emploi très compliqué et le repiquage d'enregistrement difficile. Rien de tout cela sur le LG. Mode d'emploi simple et logique. Excellente qualité de la partie magnétoscope. Grâce aux six têtes de lecture, très bon arrêt en pause de la lecture d'une bande, et le dubbing sur DVD se fait sans trace de lecture au redémarrage de la bande comme sur le Toshiba. De même pour la partie DVD, démarrage instantané en mode REC sur une émission de télévision, idem pour l'arrêt.La seule critique concerne le fait qu'il n'y ait qu'une seule prise Peritel, ce qui rend la connectique un peu compliquée si on a un ampli Home Cinéma un peu ancien sans entrée HDMI et un nombre limité d'entrées YUV déjà toutes prises. Il faut sortir par cette prise SCART .Sinon, contrairement à un commentaire fait ici, cette prise fonctionne parfaitement en entrée, à condition d'avoir le bon câble. Beaucoup de câbles SCART/SCART bas de gamme du commerce n'ont pas toutes les broches de câblées. J'ai eu des soucis dans le passé pour d'autres connexions avec ce type de câble. Mais avec un câble de marque un peu plus haut de gamme, aucun problème et on peut très bien connecter un décodeur satellite sur cette entrée répertoriée en AV1 en input.Si on a utilisé la prise SCART en sortie, il faut passer en entrée en façade par la prise AV2 qui est en RCA. Là encore il faut le bon câble, car il y a des câbles SCART/RCA en vidéo out, et d'autres en vidéos in. Il faut bien évidemment un câble en vidéo in, mais seul un câble de marque portera ces inscriptions sur les broches.Pour une autre remarque sur le SECAM, j'ai très peu de vidéos du commerce, mais sur la seule explicitement marquée comme SECAM, la lecture se fait correctement.

title: Hauppauge 1191 WinTV-HVR-955Q USB TV Tuner For Notebook
availability: Only 16 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: This review is for the most recent revision of the 950Q, purchased in January of 2012.  It's worth pointing out that this is a different package than that sold previously, with the same model number.  The back of my stick reads as follows:NTSC/ATSC/QAM HD TV receiver72001 LF Rev B4F0  4311.(It also lists a unique MAC address, which you may need if dealing with your local cable company)The box this shipped in is a smaller box than shown in the images, above, and instead of the white styrofoam insert, there's a brown corrugated cardboard insert.The stick is present, as is the little AV patch cable, and the antenna, as well as a remote.  I say "A remote" because the remote provided is NOT the remote shown in the images above.  My remote is not the type with a membrane switch face, and would not slip into the card slot of a laptop (and since those slots are not even included anymore, that makes sense).  The new remote has the same raised rubber buttons most remotes have, albeit in a small and portable form factor.  It seems as though there are a couple of buttons on the other remote which aren't present on this one, but since I can't see a close-up of the other remote, I can't be certain.The remote I was provided with seems to work fine, but there's a significant "lag" between using it and having the WinTV 7 software respond.  (By the way, this package came with the latest version of WinTV7, v2.4d, on CD, which leads me to conclude that this is a newer release, not an older one, though there's no way to be certain).The antenna seems to work better than I'd have expected, and should be more than servicable for my "travel use" needs.  I need to get a slim coax cable to travel with to patch into cable TV as well, and that's not provided here... only the antenna is provided.  But the antenna works nicely... I was able to get 16 channels here in Austin, TX, while the FCC's site suggested I could only expect to receive about ten.It's worth noting that I get more channels using the provided WinTV  application than I do when using Windows Media Center.  I fail to see why the provided application would receive more, but it does.  I get about ten channels using WMC, with the rest being "below threshold."The antenna provided is acceptable, but a better antenna will undoubtedly improve overall reception.  I plan to obtain a "leaf plus" antenna (which should be easy to carry when traveling) which will, if reports hold true, double the number of receivable stations for me.  We'll see.  Of course, a real, outdoors directional antenna would be a huge benefit, but that's impractical for a device whose main reason for existence is to be PORTABLE, after all.As several others have mentioned, the device becomes warm.  Not "HOT" (ie, you can still touch it) but it clearly draws a lot of power.  Your best bet, long-term, is to use it with an external, powered USB hub.  However, it works just fine off my little netbook's internal power.  The install guide recommends not using it with a hub, but that seems clearly to be more about power than about "lag," and going through an externally-powered hub should cause no problems.  (I plan to obtain a new 8-port powered hub later tonight, and I'll revise this review if this changes.)The remote isn't "ideal" but is acceptable.  However, I strongly recommend trying a little device made by a Chinese company called "Riitek."  You'll find several variations of that being sold on Amazon right now, and often using different names (usually the exporter selling it into the USA, not the original manufacturer, though).I have this little device in both BT and 2.4Ghz radio versions.  Unless you find the idea of using a "dongle" undesirable, I actually prefer the 2.4Ghz version overall, though they're effectively identical in most ways.  Here's the one I bought... though the name it's listed under on Amazon has changed since I bought it.http://www.amazon.com/FAVI-Entertainment-Wireless-Keyboard-TouchPad/dp/B003UE52ME/ref=cm_cr_pr_pb_tAnd here's the Blutooth version...  which is nicer, overall, but nearly identical... and which has the minor drawback of occasionally dropping connection in "blutooth-heavy" environments (like, say, airports).http://www.amazon.com/Wireless-Bluetooth-Keyboard-Cellphones-touchpad/dp/B0042VF30U/ref=sr_1_3?s=electronics&ie=UTF8&qid=1326141350&sr=1-3You'll find these sold by a number of folks on Amazon.  ALL are made by Riitek.  They're GREAT devices, frankly, and are of high-quality (unlike so many Chinese-made-and-designed objects I've dealt with over the years).  I'm very happy with them, and strongly recommend them.  Using this as a "remote mini-keyboard and mouse" easily replaces your little Hauppauge remote, especially when working with Windows Media Center.

title: Car GPS Head Up Display - Windshield Speedometer Projector HUD for All Car Models (White)
availability: Only 6 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: This heads up speedometer display is an inexpensive retrofit for older cars. Perhaps your speedometer no longer works or perhaps you just like the idea of a digital display reflected on your windshield. The unit itself is compact and shows a bright reversed LCD display with ~1 inch digits. Of course the size you see reflected will depend on the geometry of your car dash and distance from the glass etc.  Remember the display will reflect off both the inner and outer surface of your windshield producing a double image. If this annoys you the unit comes with a self-adhesive clear plastic sheet that you can attach to your screen to reduce the secondary reflection. Be careful to mount this outside of your normal driving view. There is a self-adhesive strip to permit mounting the unit to your dash once you find the perfect location. The unit requires 5V and has a USB-C socket on the long side. The unit comes with a USB-A to USB-C cable which may be long enough to reach your USB outlets but longer cables are easily available on Amazon.Now let's talk technology. This unit uses a GPS reading from "visible" satellites around you. So, it requires open sky and might not work in downtown Manhattan with skyscrapers blocking the sky and certainly will stop working inside a building like a parking structure. The other limiting factor is that the unit takes time to get a satellite fix. Thankfully it works with the US GPS system and also the Chinese Beidou satellites so a fix should be possible in most places. Some more expensive units skip GPS and plug  into the OBD port of your car from which they can read the speed info directly.For the money this is not a bad device at all. I like that there is a raised lip around the display which if positioned correctly will prevent you seeing the reversed display directly, adding to the "magic" of this inexpensive HUD.

title: Garmin 010-02157-10 fenix 6X Sapphire, Premium Multisport GPS Watch, features Mapping, Music, Grade-Adjusted Pace Guidance and Pulse Ox Sensors, Dark Gray with Black Band
availability: Only 1 left in stock - order soon.
categories: ["Electronics","GPS, Finders & Accessories","Sports & Handheld GPS","Running GPS Units"]
top_review: ******** THIS IS NOT A MEDICAL DEVICE, SO LOWER YOUR EXPECTATIONS **********To start, this is a beautiful watch. I bought it for my boyfriend for his birthday because he’s getting into fitness, and this watch has helped him track his progress and stay on path. I bought the 6X Sapphire edition in the hopes of avoiding scratches and also in the hopes of rivaling G-Shock, his original favorite. Sapphire specifically was important to me in a watch face, because sapphire, after all, is a 9 out of 10 on Mohs hardness scale. The only thing harder than a 9 is diamond, which is a 10. This reduces the chance of scratches significantly.I will include this warning in the beginning: when first unboxing it and turning it on, nothing seemed amiss – at first. It was beautiful, worked great, connected effortlessly to his phone, etc. But when he tried downloading new watch faces, a problem emerged. After many Internet searches, we learned that the software on the watch was out of date (which, looking back, probably should have been expected – these may have been sitting in a warehouse for God knows how long and it’s possible that Garmin had released some updates since that time). We were able to get the watch updated by connecting it to the power cord and plugging the cord into the computer and downloading a software update. After that, zero issues – the watch faces downloaded, widgets were added, and all was right in Whoville. 8/10Aesthetically, this thing is stunning but very large; it’s definitely (in my opinion) meant for someone with a larger wrist. It fits him very well. 10/10In the 2.5 months he’s had it, it’s never scratched. We even took a nail to it – and there was not one mark! Yeah, science! It’s also very durable; he’s dropped it, banged it on the counter countless times, submerged it in 8ft pools, and there was not one issue. 10/10As far as tracking goes, the watch has some drawbacks. It seems to track steps decently, and it seems to track heartrate and stress levels okay, but it’s not perfect. The sleep tracking isn’t always spot-on; it often calculates him going to sleep 30 minutes before he actually goes to sleep because (we theorize) his heartrate drops as his body relaxes for bed. It does calculate his information when exercising, but it’s not perfect. It does calculate his resting heartrate, but it’s not perfect. Above all, keep in mind that this is not a medical device and will, thus, not be as accurate as one. My best advice would be to make sure it’s tight but not restricting blood flow; you shouldn’t be able to slide it every which way on your arm. We think it uses a laser to track the blood pressure (or heartrate or whatever else) in the veins underneath. We even tested this theory: if he moves the watch up an inch on his arm (to where it’s covering his tattoos), the difference in tracking and reporting heartrate was very noticeable. 7/10The other features that this watch has are great. The connection to iPhone was seamless and the text/notification updates are helpful. Like others have mentioned, you don’t have the ability to text from this watch – but I think that’s a good thing, because if you were able to, you’d be giving up the water-resistant features and the shock-absorbing features that this thing has. The weather app, the elevation/altimeter, the maps, and all that other good stuff works great. If you get lost in the woods and for some reason can’t find your phone, you can use your handy-dandy watch to pull up a map and zoom out to see just where you are. It’ll give you directions, just like maps on your phone. The app store for this thing has a whole new world of little apps and widgets (Spotify, beer tracking?!) that you can play around with. 9/10I think this was a great purchase. The battery life is fantastic. Five days without a charge and it still goes strong – and when you do charge it, it only takes 30 minutes to an hour to get back up to halfway/fully charged. My main concern before buying was water damage and shock damage, but both have passed rigorous tests and this watch has proven to be very strong and durable. Also, it comes with an automatic one year limited warranty. Don't buy the warranty through Amazon. I checked with a customer service rep from Garmin's website and he confirmed that all Garmin watches come with the warranty. Overall: 9.9/10**** ONE YEAR UPDATE ****This is the single best purchase I have ever made. The watch is still going as strong as day 1. The watch band did end up breaking with normal wear and tear, but I had originally purchased a backup band for $10 when I bought the watch (which I recommend to anyone no matter what kind of watch you're buying), so that didn't ruin my day. Overall, this watch has seen a lot. Vacations, pools, accidents, workouts, and a lot of life. Friends, there is still not one scratch on it. Nothing can break it. Everything is still perfect. I am tempted to run over it with my car to see if that would even do anything (although I won't). My boyfriend wears it 24/7 except to charge it and it's become an integral part of his daily life. He sends me his workout report from his phone from Garmin Connect, and it tells you many details such as average and max heartrate, distance traveled, calories burned, and more. It has given us help when lost in the woods. It has given us the altitude as we drove through the mountains. It has monitored a 65lb weight loss journey. It has withstood the heat of fire (temporarily a hand may have been engulfed in flames; he's okay). I should be Garmin's spokesperson, honestly. Buy this damn watch. Do not do any more research. Your journey for the perfect watch ends here. This is the one!

top_review: I received this player in early June of 2023.  I loved it from the moment I got it as I was looking for something small for my bath vanity.  I was a little concerned about the third part seller with an electronic, but the company had a high customer satisfaction rating, so I ordered the unit.It's wonderful because it does so many different things, but I was mainly looking for a clock, CD player, and a radio.  The wireless charging, 2 alarms, display dimmer w/ a no display option, and the blue tooth were a bonus.  Unfortunately, after a few months of use the player controls seemed to freeze and everything stopped working.  Of course, I was past the Amazon return date, but (through their chat option) they did provide a link to begin communicating with the seller G Keni.  I was not optimistic at first and stressed through emails that I was not looking for a refund but needed technical assistance.  The people at their After Sales A/S department responded immediately and were extremely helpful.We had several emails about the issue, and they assured me that the problem would be resolved, but they wanted to know details so they could present the problem to their engineers.  They had questions to clarify which finally led to requesting photos and a video showing that the controls were frozen.  While I offered to return the unit with a prepaid label, they said that was not necessary and shipped a new player to me which arrived today September 25, 2023.While language interpretation was questionable at times (language translators were being used) overall all communications were within 24 hours, and I couldn't have asked for a better customer service experience.

title: USB C Link Cable 13ft/4m, USB3.0 A to USB Type C Cable 90 Degree 5Gbps Data Transfer USB C Charging Cable for Quest 1/2, Virtual Reality Headset Galaxy S21 S20 Note20
top_review: Top-end VR headsets connect to your computer using specialized cables, but for the Oculus Quest (and Quest 2), which is essentially a stand-alone headset, but which CAN be used with a PC as well, having a long cable like this (and the right software on both ends) can allow it to work in very much the same way.Now, to be clear... ALL this cable is, is a standard USB cable.  Nothing more, nothing less.  It has a USB 3.x Type "A" connection on one end, and a USB 3.0 Type "C" connection on the other end.  To make it easier to use with the Quest (and Quest 2) it has a right-angle connection at the "device" end (the USB-C end).  This can be strapped against the headset (a velcro-type strap is included to do just that)  to prevent inadvertent disconnection of the cable.Some sold for use with the Quest headsets have bare plastic cable insulation, but most have braided covers over that plastic cable insulation.  This one has such a braided cover, and it seems to be decent quality.  The presence of such a braided cover helps prevent inadvertent damage to the cable (which you can't SEE while wearing your VR headset, but which could easily be stepped on, or tripped over, if you're not careful!)But, in the end, this is just a USB cable, regardless of it being "tweaked" to better fulfill the specific "Quest connection" function.  And it's a good quality USB cable.  It doesn't necessarily stand out from the pack, but it's perfectly functional for what it is.The main things to look at when looking at Quest connection cables are:1)  Can the headset end be secured to the headset (in this case, yes).2)  Is the length what you need (that's entirely situational... it depends on your room, and where your PC is, in other words.)  This is the length I needed.3)  Is it robust, and not easily damaged or broken?  (Yes, this cable seems to be more than adequately robust)4)  Is it cosmetically consistent with your gaming space?  (This is a TRIVIAL issue to me, but many people  like getting one of the "right color" to match other things they have, so that's a consideration as well, I suppose.  In my case, "neutral grey" is just fine for me.  But if you really want a hot-pink cable, no doubt, you can find that, too!)

title: Sony SSCS5 3-Way 3-Driver Bookshelf Speaker System (Pair) - Black
top_review: I want to start off by saying that I have quite a bit of experience with speakers in all ranges and have quite a lot of knowledge about speakers and how audio works. And in most speakers, even 300 dollar+ sets, there's a few common issues that usually puts me off as a listener which these speakers have done a great job at avoiding.Typically speakers under $500 have the following issues:Tweeters don't mix well with the loudspeaker in the cabinet and sound like another miss-matched speaker placed ontop of your much better mid/low range speakers.Tweeters are overbearing and sound "washey" or metalic.Sound quality, especially in high frequencies, is greatly reduced when keeping the dust protection panel on.Bass is strong but lacks proper tone.Bass is weak but has gratuitous excursion.Bass has good tone, but relies too much on the addition of a subwoofer or passive resonance speakers resulting in overall lower quality lows/mids.3-way crossover makes it difficult for your amplifier to get a proper read resulting in underwhelming volumesAudio suffers greatly when not placed in the absolute most optimal position which restricts placement or quality.That's a lot of common problems and, even with the good reviews and lots of research, I expected to hear at least one of them.However I can happily say that I am blown away at how well these speakers handle all of these issues. Up close, far away, with a sub, without, placed properly or improperly, used with other speakers or alone these two mini-monsters absolutely crush all of these issues and sound dang good while doing it.I'm very critical when it comes to audio and I'd easily say that I'd have to be ready to dump 600 dollars into anything to consider an upgrade being a big enough jump to be worth it.I have these connected to an Integra Pre-Amp and are powering them with a Crown 1000 amplifier in a very large room (probably 35x30ft) . Off the rip I think 6 Ohms is perfect for this size speaker in a home theater, especially for fronts, but these go above and beyond just making a few right decisions. These clearly had ALL the good design choices... So if your amplifier can do 6 Ohms, then I'd highly recommend these.I'd also like to add that the volume and atmospheric resonance in these are comparable to 8 Ohm 350 watt speakers, so 100 watts is something my power bill is happy to adopt.These barely break a sweat producing loud, high quality, detailed sound and for once I'm not worried about heavy excursion ripping them apart.I will be using these for music at house parties as well as for movies and gaming and so far I've tested them for all three and have yet to be disappointed.Personally I would not recommend these as side speakers as they're a little TOO in your face. I think side and rear are a whole different ball game. That being said, you could definitely order 6 of these and use them as front, surround, and rear surround speakers; you'd just need to calibrate their volumes and equalize them properly.All in all, I'm proud to say I own these and even more proud to tell people what I spent on them. These aren't just great for how much they are, they're great in general. Unless you're willing to spend a lot of money, there's little-to-no audible difference between these and other very high end speakers and I personally recommend getting these speakers if your setup requires bookshelf sized speakers.Final Verdict:8.5/10 for audio quality if we completely ignore price and consider 10 the best sound imaginable.9.7/10 if I factor in price and give in to my bass-head type personality (secretly wishing these had subwoofer level bass).10/10 for anyone who isn't the pickiest SOB in the world and simply wants what 98% of the world would consider to be perfect audio.(ps: When I say the bass on these are very good I am talking about what you would expect for tone and strength coming from a Home Theater speaker. Unless you want to get those huge cabinet speakers you see in actual theaters, you are never going to get subwoofer level bass out of a front channel speaker. You simply aren't meant to, and for good reason. You do not need a sub to hear sub-frequencies with these as they handle bass incredibly well... but please do not think these can replace a woofer. They're called sub-"woofers" because they push air so hard you can feel it. That's not bass, that's an artificial effect)UPDATE:It's been 2 years and still going strong. Now of course I know a lot about the best ways to configure setups and get the most out of my speakers, but everyone who hears how good this system sounds is blown away. Almost everyone is encouraged to get a setup of their own after hearing how good it sounds. These definitely compliment my center channel and other speakers so well. It almost doesn't matter what speakers I mix with these, it just works. I've tried a few different configurations and have been pushing these hard on a weekly basis. Seems like no matter what I throw at these they just work. I also have a particularly dust-happy room; I am pleased to say that these do not have a tendency to pick up dust as I haven't had to clean them even once. Reliability, functionality, audio balance, build quality are all there. I wish I could give these more stars as I don't think people understand just how rare it is to find a speaker like this in this price range. Not usually a Sony fan, but hats off to the engineers in Japan that designed this - you guys deserve a pay raise.

top_review: My recent cable cord-cutting meant that I needed a new, desktop TV receiver for my home office--all my local channels are now coming via antenna. The Pyle had the best reviews and now I see why. The picture is excellent, sharp and bright with realistic colors. The front panel control layout is convenient. For my use, I would have preferred the jacks for power, antenna, etc. to be on the back rather than the side, but considering that this was made to give you the option on hanging on a car seat, I can understand why they chose the side.The tilting stand is a bit light, but nicely designed. With AC power, headphone output (to a small stereo system), and a heavy coax antenna connection, there's a bit of strain on it. There are some screw-holes on the base, so I do have the option of mounting the base on a piece of wood, if the wobbliness gets annoying.The remote control layout is nicer than most that I've seen for this kind of TV, which tend to be just a grid of buttons.With a basic Winegard FlatWave powered antenna, I was able to trap all the important channels even though I'm in an area where reception can be a challenge (near the antenna farm but in the shadow of a ridge). It pulled in just about as many as a Sony Bravia I have on an upper floor (with the same kind of antenna).The TV comes with an ample box of cables, adapters and connectors. At first I was a bit dismayed at the odd receptacle for the external antenna. But then, I discovered an adapter sitting at the bottom of the box 'o stuff and was quite happy. The setup was easy, once I realized that there was an on/off switch on the side panel as well as the power button on the front. This will normally run on AC power, so I can't comment on battery life until we have our first power failure of the winter.So I'm generally very happy with my selection and would recommend it.

title: AmScope 48 LED Microscope Ring Light with Dimmer - up to 61mm Mount Size - Includes 48mm Ring Adapter - for Stereo Microscopes - LED-48W
top_review: The AmScope LED-48W is a nice basic ring light which delivers diffuse cool-white illumination bright enough for low to medium magnification stereo microscopy or macro photography at working distances of 10 to 25-cm. Power is supplied by the included generic USB charger or by any convenient 1-amp USB port. A rotary switch on the case turns the light on and adjusts its intensity. The case is light-grey plastic but it does not look or feel cheap. Set screws run in threaded brass inserts. The integrated power cord is only about 45-inches long (just over 1 meter) so some users may need an AC extension cord. I have a nearby computer USB port so cord length is not an issue for me.The product specification label on the ring light case has two minor errors:“Power consumption: 0-10W” is incorrect. The ring light draws only one amp at maximum intensity so its power consumption is just 5 watts, well within the limits of common USB ports.“Working distance: 20-160mm” is misleading. LEDs are arranged along a circle with a diameter of 75mm. They are directed parallel to the visual axis and can’t evenly illuminate the center of a field at extremely close working distances. At 38mm, the center of the field is 45-degrees off axis to the LEDs. In addition, the curved inner edge of the clear plastic lens covering the LEDs produces refraction anomalies at distances less than 30mm. This will not be a problem for most users.

title: NiSi 112mm NC UV - Circular Camera Lens Protector Filter Compatible with Nikon NIKKOR Z 14-24 f/2.8 S - Ultra-Slim Brass Frame, HD Optical Glass, Waterproof Nano Coating
availability: Only 4 left in stock - order soon.
top_review: Nikon gave us a wonderful lens and brilliant filter hood design with the Z 14-24 f/2.8 S lens, but delivered a poor execution of that idea by making the hood from plastic which tends to cause filters to become stuck when the plastic bends.  The pedals of that hood prevent a filter wrench to be used to loosen filters.  NiSi has taken that idea and produced that hood from solid aluminum the way Nikon should have made it.  It's a brilliant design, filters can be applied and removed with a simple twist, the original Nikon cap fits perfectly.  This hood and filters you add work with all the holy trinity lenses: the 14-24 f/2.8 S, 24-70 f/2.8 S, and the 70-200 f/2.8 S.  It also works with the 50mm f/1.2 S.  I was a bit concerned with lock screw scratching the lens, but it only needs half a turn and doesn't need to touch the lens to lock the hood in place.  It's easier to find rather than fumble around to find a Nikon lens hood latch.  The only down side of this hood is it's slightly heavier than the standard hood, but in exchange for a little weight, you get a much better hood.
